<BODY>
<DIV1 TYPE="comedy">
<PB REF="5">
<HEAD>THE WILL: A COMEDY.</HEAD>
<DIV2 N="1" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT I.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;The Gate of Mandeville Ca&s;tle, and View of &s;ur|rounding Country.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MANDEVILLE <HI>and</HI> ROBERT.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ROBERT.</SPEAKER>
<P>JOY! I give you joy, Sir!&mdash;Once more welcome to Mandeville Ca&s;tle!&mdash;Look, Sir!&mdash;there &s;tands the old pile, ju&s;t as we left it fourteen years ago! Shall I knock at the gate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lo&s;e not a moment. <STAGE><HI>[Rob knocks.]</HI></STAGE> I have travel|led far to have the my&s;tery unravelled; and till I know why I have been thus treated&mdash;why for three tedious years I have received no letter from my father&mdash;no tidings of my child&mdash;the interval is in&s;upportable!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pretty treatment, indeed, Sir!&mdash;to bring two gen|tlemen from India&mdash;all the way from the &s;hores of Bengal to the coa&s;t of Devon&s;hire&mdash;only to get an an&s;wer to our let|ters!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't I write by every packet?&mdash;regularly remit half my pay for the &s;upport of my daughter?&mdash;And to re|ceive no an&s;wer!&mdash;to hear nothing from my father, or Mrs. Rigid, the governe&s;s of my child?&mdash;What&mdash;what can be the motive for this &s;ilence?&mdash;In India I have been guilty of no vices&mdash;no extravagance!&mdash;and if, before I
<PB N="6" REF="6">went, I involved my&s;elf in pecuniary embarra&s;&s;ments, was it not to &s;erve a friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It was, Sir!&mdash;You became &s;ecurity for the ungrate|ful Mr. Howard; and becau&s;e he took it into his head to die, and leave you re&s;pon&s;ible for twenty thou&s;and pounds&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We were compelled to fly to India!&mdash;Well, well, blame not Howard; if he had lived, he would have pro|ved him&s;elf de&s;erving of my friend&s;hip. But now, Robert, I am here once more in the centre of my creditors; and if my father has forgotten me&mdash;Knock again&mdash;the &s;u&s;pen&s;e is dreadful!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob. [knocks]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Surely they are all run away, or drowned, or hanged&mdash;Hanged!&mdash;I beg pardon, Sir!&mdash;I only al|lude to the female part of the family; and I dare &s;ay ma|ny a fair neck has been twi&s;ted in con&s;equence of my ab|&s;ence&mdash;Not come yet! Nay: don't fret &s;o, Sir: the wor&s;t come to the wor&s;t, we can but make the &s;ame exit we did this time fourteen years!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Can't you remember our &s;tealing out of tho&s;e gates in di&s;gui&s;e?&mdash;our being found out by the bailiffs, and dodging them &s;o artfully from place to place, that by the time they had taken out a writ in one county we were &s;afely perched in another; till at la&s;t, after having outwit|ted half the &s;heriffs'-officers and attorneys in England, we &s;$$ured our retreat by arriving at Port&s;mouth late on a Sa|turday night, and &s;ailing for India early on Sunday morn|ing!&mdash;Ha! ha! ha! I &s;hall never forget the Captain's &s;moking us, and after dinner giving for a toa&s;t, "Succe&s;s to the Sunday men!"</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! who comes here?&mdash;Old Realize, my fa|ther's &s;teward!&mdash;Now we &s;hall get information.&mdash;Ob&s;erve!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> REALIZE <HI>and</HI> COPSLEY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't talk to me, you old poacher! Hav'n't you been repeatedly warned off Sir Solomon's manor, and didn't he him&s;elf &s;ee you kill the hare on his ground? And therefore, at Sir Solomon's reque&s;t, I di&s;mi&s;s you from being game keeper to the Mandeville manors.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cop&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Con&s;ider, con&s;ider, Mr. Realize!&mdash;I am an old &s;ervant, and am as innocent of poaching&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<PB N="7" REF="7">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You were caught in the fact; and therefore I di&s;|mi&s;s you, and appoint in your place&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[Robert comes up to him.]</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Me, Mr. Steward!&mdash;hone&s;t Boo Tickwell!&mdash;How are you, my old friend?&mdash;how are you?&mdash;Here we are, you &s;ee, hot from Bengal!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, it can't be!&mdash;Yes: it is!&mdash;The long look|ed for come at la&s;t!&mdash;Huzza!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Realize, I am glad to &s;ee you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So am I to &s;ee you; and &s;o will Sir Solomon; and &s;o will all the neighbours.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There!&mdash;I &s;aid &s;o!&mdash;I knew we &s;hould have a joy|ous welcome!&mdash;Come! open wide the Ca&s;tle gates, and prepare the wine&mdash;the veni&s;on&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Open wide the pri&s;on gates, and prepare the bread and water!&mdash;Mr. Mandeville <STAGE><HI>[to Mand.],</HI></STAGE> Sir, I'll trouble you for that two hundred pounds you owe me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha!&mdash;this isn't a proper time&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where is my money, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Non&s;en&s;e! His father will &s;atisfy you.&mdash;Come&mdash;we'll all pay the old gentleman a vi&s;it together.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Laying hold of Realize's arm.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Softly, ma&s;ter Robert.&mdash;You may both go to the old gentleman as &s;oon as you like; but, for me, I don't in|tend to pay him a vi&s;it the&s;e twenty years.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No!&mdash;Why, where is he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where, I can't exactly &s;ay&mdash;only I fancy you are about as far from him now as when you were hot in Bengal.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What, is he gone abroad?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No; he's gone home!&mdash;he's dead!&mdash;defunct!&mdash;was buried twelve months ago!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dead!&mdash;my father dead!&mdash;I didn't expect this.</P>
<STAGE><HI>Putting his handkerchief to his eyes.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No more did I, Sir&mdash;Oh! h! h!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[weeping violently.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, what's the milk&s;op crying at?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'm crying to think what trouble old Mr. Mande|ville's death will occa&s;ion to my poor ma&s;ter&mdash;What a fa|tigue it will be to collect in all the rent$&mdash;to pay his debts&mdash;to di&s;charge you, and appoint me &s;teward in your place&mdash;Oh! h! h!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!&mdash;If that's all that afflicts you, dry up your tears, booby&mdash;Your ma&s;ter is di&s;inherited.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="8" REF="8">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;inherited!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Cut off with a &s;hilling!&mdash;Mr. Mandeville has left his whole e&s;tate to a woman.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A woman!&mdash;Oh! the old profligate!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To your child, Sir <STAGE><HI>[to Mandeville]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;to his own grand daughter!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To Albina!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Bravo!&mdash;Then it comes to the &s;ame point! my ma&s;|ter of cour&s;e manages the property, and I'm &s;teward &s;till.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There you're out again! I rather think Mrs. Rigid will manage the property. I rather imagine the young Heire&s;s will be ruled by the old Governe&s;s; and as you've been no friend to her, Mr. Mandeville&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No friend to her!&mdash;How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay: perhaps you may call it friend&s;hip to leave her to &s;upport your daughter at her own expence; perhaps you may call it friend&s;hip, not to write any letters, or re|mit any money, for three years together.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Go on, Sir; let me know all.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why then you may know, that Mrs. Rigid inform|ed the late Mr. Mandeville of your unfatherlike conduct; that he invited her and his grand daughter to his hou&s;e, and taking a fancy to Mi&s;s Albina, he made her his hei|re&s;s. There now you've heard the whole &s;tory; and I &s;hall call it friend&s;hip, if you'll pay me my two hundred pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not write letters!&mdash;Not remit money!&mdash;Hear me, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not now. The Heire&s;s is expected from Dover every moment, and I mu&s;t go and prepare the Ca&s;tle for her reception. Come along, Poacher; come and deliver your keys to your &s;ucce&s;&s;or&mdash;I'll take out a writ direct|ly, and he &s;ha'n't &s;lip through my fingers a &s;econd time&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[a&s;ide.]</HI></STAGE> No more di&s;gui&s;es, Mr. Mandeville&mdash;No more Sunday men, Mr. Steward.&mdash;"Oh! what trouble will the old gentleman's death occa&s;ion to my poor ma&s;ter!"</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Mi|$icking Robert, and exit with Cop&s;ley at the Ca&s;tle gate.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now all's out, Sir. No wonder at our not receiv|ing an&s;wers, when they &s;ay we &s;ent no letters. Oh that diabolical Governe&s;s! I always &s;aid you were to blame, to place your only child under her care; particularly when
<PB N="9" REF="9">you knew &s;he was once in love with you, and you refu&s;ed her, and married her cou&s;in, Mi&s;s Herbert.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, name not her! If my Amelia had &s;urvived, I &s;hould not have been doomed unheard!&mdash;What! de&s;ert|ed! di&s;inherited!&mdash;Is this my welcome home? Am I to find a father dead, and dying full of re&s;entment again&s;t me? a daughter prejudiced! nay, perhaps cur&s;ing my ve|ry name, and this Governe&s;s&mdash;Speak, Sir; ju&s;tify your injured ma&s;ter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will with my life, Sir; but don't be &s;atisfied with Realize's &s;tory: let us get information el&s;ewhere. Yonder is the hou&s;e of Sir Solomon Cynic. If the old gentleman hasn't fretted away his life by railing at the follies of wo|mankind, perhaps he lives to con&s;ole and befriend you. Shall we go to him, Sir?.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Take me where you will <STAGE><HI>[Going, &s;tops].</HI></STAGE> Robert, how old was Albina when we la&s;t &s;aw her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Rob.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>About four years, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And I left her in the fond hope, that I might one day find in her a recompen&s;e for the lo&s;s of her mother! And now if I behold her, &s;he will avoid&mdash;upbraid me! That thought is pa&s;t all bearing. I'll know the wor&s;t, and then my fate's decided. They may de&s;ert, but they &s;hall not de&s;pi&s;e me!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE.</HI>&mdash;An Apartment in <HI>Sir SOLOMON'S</HI> Hou&s;e.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir SOLOMON, <HI>followed by</HI> CICELY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, it's in vain&mdash;your application's u&s;e|le&s;s&mdash;your whole &s;ex is u&s;ele&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Sir Solomon&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you women are of no u&s;e&mdash;none! but to nur&s;e children, mend linen, make puddings, and beat their hu&s;bands.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>But con&s;ider, your Honour, the hare was killed by accident, not by de&s;ign; the dogs cha&s;ed it into your grounds; and I hope Mr. Realize won't di&s;mi&s;s my poor father.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Keep off&mdash;keep within your magic circle&mdash;I hav'n't been within the reach of a woman the&s;e twenty years; and you are the very la&s;t I'd &s;uffer to come near
<PB N="10" REF="10">me. I have often ob&s;erved you in my walks&mdash;often noted your mi&s;chievous &s;miles, your penetrating eyes, and I don't like them; I &s;ay, I don't like them; &s;o keep your di&s;tance. I won't be made a fool of a &s;econd time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;econd time, Sir Solomon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye; I was once as much in love as Mark An|tony, and like him I was de&s;erted by my Cleopatra. His queen cho&s;e a mighty conqueror to be fal&s;e with; but my Su&s;annah, my fanta&s;tic Su&s;annah, fixed her affections on a dancing-ma&s;ter&mdash;a caperer! and ever &s;ince I have had &s;uch a contempt for the &s;ex&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Cicely lays hold of his hand.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Holloa! you touched me! I feel the &s;hock&mdash;I'm electrified&mdash;I'm&mdash;What &s;weet lips the gip&s;y has!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you would only pay a vi&s;it to our cottage, and be eye witne&s;s to the di&s;tre&s;s you will occa&s;ion! Your ne|phew Mr. Howard has often been there; and if you would come and imitate his charitable conduct, I and my &s;i&s;ters would be &s;o grateful&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Still laying hold of his hand.]</HI></STAGE></P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;i&s;ters! Pooh! non&s;en&s;e! what &s;hould I do among a parcel of young giddy, romping&mdash;Hark'ye! are all your &s;i&s;ters as hand&s;ome as your&s;elf?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hand&s;ome! How you flatter, Sir Solomon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I don't&mdash;You're the mo&s;t lovely, mo&s;t bewitching&mdash;Su&s;annah was a dowdy to you! Look here, now&mdash;look at the omnipotence of Love! a man is never &s;ecure from its in$$u$nce; and if he live$ independent of the &s;ex till he is &s;o old and decrepid that he cannot &s;tir from his bed, yet then, even then, he may fall a victim to its power.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis Mr. Howard!&mdash;Now I'll a$$ him to intercede for me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Howard!&mdash;So it is? and &s;omebody with him&mdash;Go&mdash;don't let us be &s;een together&mdash;I'll come to the cot|tage &s;oon after &s;un &s;et, and if the h$re was really killed by accident&mdash;Hu&s;h!&mdash;begone&mdash;no care&s;&s;ing&mdash;we'll re|&s;erve all that for by and by&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Cicely exit.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;So, I have once more the true Mark Antony feel.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MANDEVILLE <HI>and</HI> HOWARD.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'ye, George! don't let me hear of your paying any more vi&s;$$s at the gamekeeper's cottage&mdash;if I
<PB N="11" REF="11">do, a certain young lady &s;hall know of your incon&s;tancy&mdash;your&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Sees Mand.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Ha! who's that?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A &s;tranger, Sir, that&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stranger!&mdash;Why, it's Mandeville!&mdash;that pro|fligate Mandeville!&mdash;What brought you from India, Sir?&mdash;And after what has pa&s;&s;ed, how dare you &s;hew your face in my hou&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How!&mdash;You again&s;t me too!&mdash;what have I done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What have you not done, Sir? Hav'n't you de|&s;erted your own child?&mdash;Hav'n't you left the Governe&s;s to maintain her at her own expence?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis fal&s;e: on my life, 'tis fal&s;e!&mdash;I wrote letter after letter&mdash;made repeated remittances; 'till, receiving no an&s;wer, and unable to endure &s;uch torturing &s;u&s;pen&s;e, I came at all hazards to England, to know why I was &s;o har&s;hly treated.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And now you know that your father has made Albina his heire&s;s&mdash;that &s;he is &s;hortly to be married to Mr. Veritas&mdash;to this gentleman's tutor, Sir. And you may al&s;o know, that I expect you in&s;tantly to di&s;charge the late Mr. Howard's debt for twelve hundred pounds.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Howard's debt!&mdash;my father's?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir: Mr. Mandeville was his &s;urety. I have his bond; and had he behaved as he ought, I'd have died rather than have a&s;ked him for it: but now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter $word$</HI> SERVANT <HI>in livery.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Serv.</HI> Sir,</SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Albina and her Governe&s;s are this mo|ment arrived at the Ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are they? I'll wait upon them directly. Mr. Mandeville, don't expect to &s;ee your daughter; for, till &s;he, is married to the Tutor, Mrs. Rigid means to &s;eclude her from all &s;ociety.&mdash;And for you, George Howard, you mu&s;t not a&s;&s;ociate with a man of his character. Though your father behaved ill to him, remember you are not re|&s;pon&s;ible for his ingratitude.&mdash;Now for the Ca&s;tle&mdash;next for the Cottage, and then&mdash;All for Love, or the World well lo&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then all's confirmed; and I've no hope&mdash;no friend!&mdash;What's to be done&mdash;Whither &s;hall I go?&mdash;where fly?&mdash;Who will receive &s;o lo&s;t a wretch as I am?&mdash;Pur|&s;ued
<PB N="12" REF="12">by enemies&mdash;abandoned by a father&mdash;for&s;aken by my child!&mdash;who will, who dare befriend me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You have forgot me, Mr. Mandeville&mdash;I &s;ee you have&mdash;You don't recollect George Howard, whom, when a boy you u&s;ed to take &s;uch notice of&mdash;I'm &s;trangely altered &s;ince you went to India&mdash;that is, in per&s;on only, I hope; for in mind and di&s;po&s;ition I am &s;till the &s;ame.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Mr. Mandeville! I don't know why&mdash;whe|ther it is from the joy at &s;eeing you, or from the grief I feel at the cruel treatment you've received&mdash;I don't know which it is&mdash;but I'm going to be the &s;ame blubbering boy you left me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!&mdash;'Sdeath! this genero&s;ity afflicts me more than all their cruelty!&mdash;Let me go!&mdash;I heard your uncle's orders&mdash;"You mu&s;t not a&s;&s;ociate with a man of his cha|racter."&mdash;Let me begone. I will not involve you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not involve me! Didn't my father involve you? And if I've not the fortune to repay the obligation, I'll prove I have the gratitude to remember it. From this hour I am devoted to your &s;ervice: and if the friend&s;hip of the &s;on can atone for the injuries of the parent, I &s;hall be far happier in partaking your di&s;tre&s;s than in &s;haring my unfeeling uncle's riches.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am mo&s;t grateful: but I cannot con&s;ent&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You mu&s;t&mdash;you &s;hall con&s;ent!&mdash;Come, come&mdash;your ca&s;e is not &s;o lo&s;t as you imagine. The Gover|ne&s;s isn't the only per&s;on who has an influence over your daughter&mdash;there is another&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who? This Tutor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No; his Pupil. I flatter my&s;elf Albina has no &s;light partiality for her father's friend.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>For you! How, and where, did you know her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you. When I and my Tutor arrived from the grand tour, we found Albina and the Governe&s;s at Dover. Mr. Veritas and Mrs. Rigid being related, we often paid them vi&s;its; and while the &s;choolma&s;ter and &s;choolmi&s;tre&s;s morali&s;ed on the mi&s;eries of the world, their two &s;cholars as naturally conver&s;ed on its plea&s;ures. In &s;ho$$, we &s;oon laughed our&s;elves into an attachment;
<PB N="13" REF="13">which the Governe&s;s perceiving, Albina was locked up, I turned out, and the Tutor de&s;tined for her hu&s;band.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!&mdash;And did &s;he&mdash;forgive my weakne&s;s, Sir&mdash;did &s;he once name her father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Often: but the Governe&s;s has in&s;tilled into her young mind &s;uch notions of your barbarity, and at the &s;ame time of her own benevolence that &s;he looks on her as a pa|rent; you as an enemy. However, don't de&s;pair&mdash;if we can once gain an interview&mdash;And what &s;ay you? Shall we go to the Ca&s;tle directly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Twill be in vain. The gates will be &s;hut again&s;t us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Never mind: we'll force them open. Come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay: but con&s;ider you are dependent on your uncle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No matter. The hope that the name of How|ard may &s;till be dear to him, who now has &s;o much cau&s;e to cur&s;e it, makes me &s;uperior to all &s;elfi&s;h thoughts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is it po&s;&s;ible? You that have had a fa&s;hionable education! you that have been &s;chooled in all the arts of modern foppery, and foreign folly! you to be the only one to pity or befriend me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, the fact is, they tried hard to &s;poil me; but I wouldn't let them&mdash;they &s;ent me all over the Conti|nent, before I'd been half over England; taught me fo|reign languages, before I knew my own; in&s;tructed me how to pick my teeth all the morning in Bond &s;treet; yawn all night at the Opera. But I was a bad &s;cholar, Mr. Mandeville: and the &s;atisfaction I feel at this moment proves I did right to educate my&s;elf.&mdash;Now then for Albi|na! They may have perverted my head; but I a&s;&s;ure you they hav'n't corrupted my heart.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF ACT I.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="2" TYPE="act">
<PB N="14" REF="14">
<HEAD>ACT II.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A modern Apartment in the Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> VERITAS <HI>and</HI> Mrs. RIGID.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>YES, yes: Albina already thinks me the be&s;t of women, and &s;hall &s;oon believe that you are the fir&s;t of men.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Granted&mdash;But about Howard&mdash;Is &s;he as fond of him as ever?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No; &s;he don't like him half &s;o well as &s;he did. Ever &s;ince he left Dover, I have been undermining him, and extolling you; and in proof of my argument, Sir Solomon has ju&s;t told her of Howard's intimacy with a gamekeeper's daughter. This has rou&s;ed her jealou&s;y&mdash;her indignation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes; and as he has now lo&s;t her affections&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I may &s;oon win them!&mdash;Bravo, Ma&s;ter Veritas!&mdash;You're lord and ma&s;ter of ten thou&s;and a year!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ten thou&s;and!&mdash;Heyday! Have you forgot our agreement? Plea&s;e to recollect, that on the day of your marriage with Albina I am to receive half?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Half?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure.&mdash;What other motive could I have for getting Mandeville di&s;inherited? Did not Albi|na gain the property through my management? Did not I make a dupe of the grandfather?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And why do I give you my intere&s;t;?&mdash;Why do I &s;elect you for her hu&s;band?&mdash;Why, but becau&s;e you are to give me a moiety?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Granted. We'll divide the fortune&mdash;and thus I &s;eal the bargain&mdash;thus with a righteous ki&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid. [Drawing back.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How! Is the man out of his &s;en&s;es?&mdash;Don't you recollect&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do.&mdash;I beg pardon&mdash;You're for the Platonic.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I <HI>am</HI> for the Platonic &s;y&s;tem, Sir, and hi|therto
<PB N="15" REF="15">I have not &s;uffered my lips to be profaned by man!&mdash;Never, Sir!&mdash;Not &s;o much from fear of the con&s;equences to my&s;elf, as from the danger in which it might involve all mankind.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's true philanthropy, Mrs. Rigid; and the longer you per&s;evere in your &s;y&s;tem, the more our &s;ex will be obliged to you&mdash;Ha! here comes Albina!&mdash;Pray in &s;he al&s;o for the Platonic?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sweet little innocent! She has hardly &s;en&s;e enough to di&s;criminate one pa&s;&s;ion from another. She is the mo&s;t artle&s;s, lively, tender-hearted creature! Look at her, cou&s;in&mdash;only eighteen!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ALBINA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Governe&s;s! I have been all over the Ca&s;tle, looking at the rooms&mdash;the pictures&mdash;the&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Seeing Veritas, &s;he &s;tops.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis Mr. Veritas. You &s;aw him at Dover, you know.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So I did; he was there at the &s;ame time Mr. How|ard was.&mdash;Oh, Lord! I'm &s;o happy to &s;ee you, Sir!&mdash;I am indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Granted. She loves me!&mdash;Poor pupil! Poor Howard!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[A&s;ide to Mrs. Rigid.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That I am, becau&s;e now I &s;hall hear &s;omething about Mr. Howard. <STAGE><HI>[To Veritas.]</HI></STAGE> Pray, Mr. Tutor&mdash;fir&s;t we'll talk of his looks, if you plea&s;e&mdash;is he as hand&s;ome now?&mdash;as charming as ever?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>For &s;hame, Albina!&mdash;After what you have ju&s;t heard from Sir Solomon, how can you conde&s;cend to name him? Did not he tell you of his pa&s;&s;ion for a game|keeper's daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He did; but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What, Mi&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That pa&s;&s;ion may be only Platonic, you know, Go|verne&s;s!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye: let me hear no more of Mr. How|ard! If you mention his name again, I'll re&s;ort to my old mode of puni&s;hment&mdash;I'll &s;hew you I have not forgot the art of looking up, Mi&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There now! I thought it would come to this! The
<PB N="16" REF="16">owner of this immen&s;e ca&s;tle will pa&s;s mo&s;t of her days in one of the clo&s;ets!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No murmuring!&mdash;but go directly with this worthy man&mdash;walk with him to &s;ee the park&mdash;the planta|tions.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, &s;ince it mu&s;t be &s;o,&mdash;come, Mr.&mdash;Worthy.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver. [A&s;ide to Albina.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mum! I am not what I &s;eem&mdash;When we're alone I'll communicate.&mdash;Cou&s;in, we take our leave.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Madam, good day!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Going.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir SOLOMON.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Sir Solomon! You're the very per&s;on I wanted to &s;ee.&mdash;Do you know, there's an old man in the hall, who &s;ays he was &s;ervant to my grandfather thirty years; and now, becau&s;e his dogs killed a hare on your grounds, that he is di&s;mi&s;&s;ed from his place, and he and his family mu&s;t &s;tarve!&mdash;Dear!&mdash;If all your game is purcha&s;ed at &s;o high a price, I wonder you're not choaked!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Go where I ordered you, Mi&s;s. Sir Solo|mon and I have bu&s;ine&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And, Sir&mdash;Sir Solomon! How came you to trouble your&s;elf about Mr. Howard's love affairs?&mdash;I tell you what&mdash;I believe you're a great poacher; and if I catch you &s;naring any game on my manor&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Begone, Mi&s;s!&mdash;Begone directly!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well: I'm going, Governe&s;s&mdash;I'm going. Come, Mr. Tutor; and if we meet that poor old man by the way. I'll tell him he may kill all the game on my e&s;tate; and if that won't keep his family from &s;tarving. I'll bid him &s;hoot all Sir Solomon's! I have plenty of money, and I can't di&s;po&s;e of it better than in protecting an old favourite of him who gave it me!&mdash;Come&mdash;good bye.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Veritas and Albina exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Um!&mdash;There's the &s;ex&mdash;There's true woman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I mu&s;t watch her&mdash;her di&s;po&s;ition alters with her fortune. But, Sir Solomon, now we're alone, what is the &s;ecret you promi&s;ed to communicate to me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll tell you&mdash;Mandeville is arrived&mdash;I've &s;een him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Seen Mandeville!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not half an hour ago&mdash;He is now in &s;earch of his daughter.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="17" REF="17">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mandeville come home!&mdash;Mercy! What &s;hall we do? Why, if he once gets hold of her, he'll per|&s;uade her to pay his debts&mdash;trick her out of the whole for|tune!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know it. He's a &s;ad profligate; and therefore do you lock up Albina, and I'll lock up Mandeville. We'll keep them apart, till &s;he has got a hu&s;band to protect her. I'll go directly, and order Realize to take out a writ.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I will.&mdash;Od&s;heart!&mdash;it was the wi&s;h of my life that Howard &s;hould marry Albina; but his attachment to other women &s;hews he is not worthy her affections; and his now a&s;&s;ociating with her father, proves he would wa&s;te every &s;hilling of the property&mdash;Therefore, the &s;ooner &s;he marries Mr. Veritas, the better. Adieu!&mdash;Go and lock her up.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I won't lo&s;e a moment.&mdash;Ah, Sir Solo|mon! If Mr. Howard had copied the example of his un|cle!&mdash;If, like you, he had never a&s;&s;ociated with profligate men, or low bred women!&mdash;You would not have fixed your affections on a game keeper's daughter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Me!&mdash;Lord help you!&mdash;How could you &s;up|po&s;e &s;uch a thing?</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Confu&s;ed.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I don't &s;uppo&s;e it. I know &s;he is too un|poli&s;hed&mdash;too illiterate&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! She's too young&mdash;too&mdash;too every thing!&mdash;No, Mrs. Rigid, if ever I again become a &s;lave to the tender pa&s;&s;ions, I &s;hould &s;elect a woman of your time of life&mdash;a woman of experience!&mdash;Your young things take no pains to plea&s;e a man; they rely on their youth and beauty: but your middle aged woman&mdash;&s;he is &s;o indu&s;tri|ours!&mdash;&s;he dre&s;&s;es at you, talks at you, glances at you&mdash;.&mdash;Oh! Time makes women wonderfully dextrons in the art of love!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[Exeunt. Mrs. Rigid ogling Sir Solomon]</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A Garden.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> VERITAS <HI>and</HI> ALBINA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha!&mdash;I told you I was not what I &s;eem|ed. It was very well to out on the ma&s;k of learning, and gravity before Sir Solomon and Mrs. Rigid; but now I'll pull it off&mdash;now I'll &s;hew you my real character!&mdash;Ble&s;s you!&mdash;I'm an hone&s;t fellow!&mdash;I'm a choice &s;pirit&mdash;a buck of the fir&s;t water!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="18" REF="18">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And pray, Sir, what made a man of your gaiety become an u&s;her?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You &s;hall hear:&mdash;I fini&s;hed my fortune before I fini&s;hed my education. At We&s;tmin&s;ter School I found I could keep a curricle: at Oxford I found I could keep a pack of hounds; and in London I found&mdash;I could not keep my&s;elf.&mdash;So not wi&s;hing &s;o much talent &s;hould re|main in ob&s;curity, I &s;et up for Tutor, in order to di&s;per&s;e my knowledge among&s;t the ri&s;ing generation.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Upon my word, the ri&s;ing generation is very much obliged to you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay: if I have not done much good, I have done little harm; for with all my follies, of this you may be a&s;|&s;ured&mdash;I never did right without rejoicing at it, or wrong without repenting it. This is my hi&s;tory. And now to apply my talents to the right purpo&s;e&mdash;to love!&mdash;Here's Mrs. Rigid.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter Mrs.</HI> RIGID.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Cou&s;in, a word&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Takes Veritas a&s;ide]</HI></STAGE> Man|deville is returned from India: he and Howard are now in &s;earch of Albina; and if an interview takes place we are undone. Go; and if you find Mandeville, give notice to Realize, and he'll arre&s;t him in&s;tantly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Arre&s;t him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure. What does the man &s;tart at? Have you any objection?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, I think, when a gentleman comes a long journey&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That a &s;punging-hou&s;e is a bad &s;ort of inn to put up at!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How! are you only half a &s;inner?&mdash;Do you repent our bargain?&mdash;Mighty well, Sir! mighty well! A fine girl and five thou&s;and a year isn't likely long to want a hu&s;band&mdash;Others may be found, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Granted.&mdash;Others may be found; and five thou&s;and a year is not to be de&s;pi&s;ed. Be&s;ides, I &s;hall make amends by making her a good hu&s;band. So I'll &s;wal|low my &s;cruples, and go directly&mdash;Cou&s;in, your &s;er|vant!&mdash;Mi&s;s Albina, adieu!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<PB N="19" REF="19">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Albina, I beg you will in&s;tantly accompany me to the Ca&s;tle; and, for rea&s;ons which I will hereafter explain to you, I mu&s;t reque&s;t you to live in private&mdash;neither to pay nor receive vi&s;its.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lord! I know your rea&s;ons well enough; you want me not to &s;ee Mr. Howard&mdash;Well! I do love him, that's the truth on't: but if he don't love me, what can I do, you know?&mdash;No! I had rather not &s;ee him&mdash;'twill remind me of pa&s;t happine&s;s; and if he be &s;hut out from me, the more private I live the better.&mdash;Come, I'll think of him no more.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Spoke like a girl of proper pride and exalt|ed &s;pirit!&mdash;Now all's &s;afe!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[As they are going, How|ard enters.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So! I've found you at la&s;t, Albina!&mdash;I called at the Ca&s;tle, and the &s;ervants told me they had orders from Doctor Bu&s;by not to admit me.&mdash;I beg pardon, Mrs. Rigid&mdash;I didn't allude to you&mdash;I didn't mean to call you Doctor Bu&s;by.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>None of your in&s;olence, Sir&mdash;Albina is no more willing to be troubled with your company than I am.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Isn't &s;he?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No:&mdash;you may hear your di&s;mi&s;&s;al from her own mouth.&mdash;Speak, child; repeat to him what you imparted to me this moment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I can't. Do you &s;peak for me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Repeat it, I tell you: &s;hew him you don't care for him: &s;ay you are all gaiety and cheerfulne&s;s&mdash;Say &s;o, I in&s;i&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir! Sir! I am all gaiety and cheerfulne&s;s! I'm &s;o happy that&mdash;Oh! Oh! Oh! <STAGE><HI>[Bur&s;ts into tears.]</HI></STAGE> I &s;hall break my heart&mdash;that's what I &s;hall!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So! This is a new mode of being cheerful!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ideot! baby! call forth your pride: re|member your rank&mdash;your fortune!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fortune! What's the u&s;e of it, while another is heire&s;s to his affections? If the game keeper's daughter will give me his heart, I'm &s;ure I'll give her my e&s;tate. Oh! Mr. Howard!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Going up to him]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid. [Laying hold of her.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This isn't to be borne! Come with me this moment!&mdash;Stand out of the way, Sir! Come, I command you.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="20" REF="20">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hold! <STAGE><HI>[Detaining Albina.]</HI></STAGE> It isn't on my own account I thus rudely detain you; 'tis on your father's.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My father's!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He is arrived from India, unfortunate man!&mdash;is now in the neighbourhood.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is he? We'll go to him directly. Come Gover|ne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Go to him! Are you mad? Why he'll a&s;k you to pay all his debts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No, he won't: for I'll offer it long before he can a&s;k me. Come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have a care: don't go near him: I know him to be &s;o unprincipled, and &s;o de&s;perate, that if you refu&s;e to give him up your fortune, I &s;houldn't be &s;urpri&s;|ed if he threatened; nay, actually took away your life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Took away my life! Well! he gave it me, you know, Governe&s;s; and as to the fortune, that certainly ought to have been his. However, as I never did, not ever will di&s;obey you, I'll tell you how we'll accommodate matters: Mr. Howard will be kind enough to &s;ay that you won't allow me to &s;ee him; but that, as to money&mdash;Lord! he may have what he likes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What he likes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye: bid him draw for a good round &s;um at once&mdash;fifty thou&s;and to begin with. And if that won't do&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! fifty thou&s;and will do very well for a be|ginning! Won't it, Doctor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me, Albina. Would you undo your|&s;elf, and abandon me? I, who have nur&s;ed you, reared you, doted on you? I, who have been a mother when he proved no father!&mdash;Go, ungrateful girl! give all to him who for&s;ook you, and leave her who cheri&s;hed you to &s;tarve, and die in a pri&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Die in a pri&s;on! Leave my kind, good Governe&s;s to die in a pri&s;on?&mdash;Oh, Lord! I can't bear the thought of it! <STAGE><HI>[Mrs Rigid w$rps.]</HI></STAGE> Nay, don't cry &s;o&mdash;&s;peak to me&mdash;pray &s;peak&mdash;Dear! What was it &s;he &s;aid, Mr. Howard?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She &s;aid you'd better give me the fifty thou|&s;and directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Millions cannot &s;ave a man &s;o extravagant as Mr. Mandeville&mdash;This was your grand father's opinion; and he left you the e&s;tate &s;olely to prevent his wa&s;ting it;
<PB N="21" REF="21">and now would you fly in the face of your benefactor? And for what? Only becau&s;e a faithle&s;s lover takes the part of a &s;elfi&s;h parent, who, till you became affluent, ne|ver thought or enquired after you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's very true.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It's not&mdash;it's fal&s;e.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know better, Sir! But for this good woman, I might have &s;tarved, and I'm bound to fulfil the intentions of my dear grandfather; and therefore&mdash;Don't take on &s;o, my dear Governe&s;s, and I'll follow your advice in every thing&mdash;Don't keep twitching me, Mr. Howard!&mdash;I &s;hall do whatever &s;he orders me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You will, will you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: I act differently from you, Sir&mdash;I always obey my tutor, and I won't&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And you won't &s;kip a ta&s;k or go out of bounds, for fear of being whipped! hah!&mdash;Oh! the good child! Oh the pretty Mi&s;s Albina! &s;he &s;hall have cakes and toys, and&mdash;Look'ye&mdash;give over this childi&s;h non&s;en&s;e, and go with me to the game-keeper's cottage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The game-keeper's cottage?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard. [Taaking hold of her hand.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There your father is concealed; I left him under the care of Cop&s;ley's daugh|ther, one of the kinde&s;t, be&s;t di&s;po&s;ed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Taking away her hand.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Go, Sir!&mdash;I'm &s;atisfied, and I hate you&mdash;that's what I do&mdash;I hate you more than ever I loved you&mdash;Come, Governe&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, Albina?&mdash;Why?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have as much pride as your&s;elf, Sir;&mdash;and &s;ince you treat me with indifference, I &s;hall treat you with &s;corn &mdash;with &s;corn. Sir!&mdash;Come, Madam.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Sdeath!&mdash;What have I &s;aid?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Quite enough, Sir!&mdash;Go to your darling ru&s;tic&mdash;go to your dear Mr. Mandeville; and, by way of con&s;olation tell him that if ever you po&s;&s;e&s;s an e&s;tate&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If ever I do, Madam, he &s;hall have it all. And I'll give it him, not &s;o much from motives of benevolence, as of prudence; &s;ince I perceive that money can transform the mo&s;t liberal to the mo&s;t &s;elfi&s;h; and &s;he who, without a fortune, was all innocence, tenderne&s;s and affection, is, in affluence, &s;u&s;picious, credulous, and unfeeling&mdash;Fare|well!&mdash;
<PB N="22" REF="22">Mandeville has a child &s;till; for, while you are a &s;lave to a Governe&s;s, I'll be a &s;on to your Father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This is your re&s;olution, is it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It is, mo&s;t potent, grave, and reverend Doctor!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Albina, look at the advantages of a good education&mdash;How contemptible was Howard's con|duct!&mdash;How noble yours!&mdash;Continue to behave thus, and you &s;hall be indulged in every thing.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah! I wi&s;h you would indulge me, Governe&s;s&mdash; There is a favour&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is there?&mdash;Name it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you already think me a good girl; but if I could be quite po&s;itive about Mr. Howard's incon&s;tancy, I &s;hould be the very be&s;t girl in the whole world.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! do you &s;till doubt?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How can I help it? How can I think &s;o meanly of him, or my&s;elf, as to &s;uppo&s;e he would prefer a girl that's like&mdash;in &s;hore, that I dare &s;ay is as unlike me as you are to Doctor Bu&s;by?&mdash;Come now, as he's gone to the cot|tage, do let me follow him and be convinced.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Follow him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why not? Look'ye: you and Sir Solomon &s;ay he is guilty. Very well! If I find him &s;o, I'll promi&s;e to marry the Steward, the Par&s;on, or the Birch Gentleman&mdash; any, or all of them, if you like.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There's no doubt of his guilt, and this may complete her aver&s;ion; therefore I'll let her go. <STAGE><HI>[A&s;ide.]</HI></STAGE> Well! on the&s;e conditions, I've no objection. But how will you contrive?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! he &s;ha'n't know me&mdash;I'll put on another dre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Another dre&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: I'll di&s;gui&s;e my&s;elf as the Little Red Riding Hood, Little John, Little Pickle, or any other impudent character&mdash;Come!&mdash;we'll &s;ettle that as we go along: and if I &s;ind him innocent, why, you &s;hall have one half the e&s;tate; my father the other; and I and Mr. Howard will live and die in the cottage, or any other retired &s;pot you choo&s;e to point out for us.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF ACT II.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="3" TYPE="act">
<PB N="23" REF="23">
<HEAD>ACT III.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;View of an open Country&mdash;River&mdash;Cottage at a di&s;tance, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MANDEVILLE <HI>and</HI> HOWARD.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>MAND.</SPEAKER>
<P>NAY: nay: blame not Albina! Blame the Governe&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not blame her!&mdash;Oh! if I look, or &s;peak, or li&s;ten, or&mdash;'Sdeath! you don't know half the fatal con|&s;equences of her unfilial conduct!&mdash;Sir Solomon has order|ed Realize to arre&s;t you: he and bailiffs are now in &s;earch of you; and, unle&s;s you can in&s;tantly rai&s;e two thou&s;and pounds, you'll be impri&s;oned!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well: I am re&s;igned.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So am not I. I hate a gaol; and as I mu&s;t follow you wherever you go, pray let us keep in the open air as long as we can. The fact is, there is no &s;taying here without paying your creditors; therefore let's adjourn to London&mdash;There we may do as we like.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do as we like?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye: few people think of paying there. Why, if every man in London were to be arre&s;ted for the money he owed!&mdash;Mercy on us!&mdash;there'd be more pri&s;ons than carriages; more bailiffs than hor&s;es; and men of fa&s;hion and da&s;hing citizens would be the two rate&s;t commodities to be met with! Oh! when a man is in debt, the Capital is the place of lie &s;ou$ in! Therefore let's begone directly. Stop though&mdash;Have you any ca&s;h?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not a guinea. Out of my pay as an officer, I could hardly &s;ave money enough to land me in my native country.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And I have not a &s;hilling!&mdash;And here we are two hundred miles from Hyde Park Corner, without two hundred pence to take us there! What's to be done? Will Sir Solomon advance? Not a halfpenny!&mdash;Will the Tutor? Not a farthing!&mdash;Will Realize?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="24" REF="24">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Steward!&mdash;He wouldn't give half-a-crown to &s;ave both our lives.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not half-a-crown to &s;ave our lives! Come&mdash; come&mdash;you wrong him there&mdash;I'm &s;ure he'd give more to &s;ave mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>More to &s;ave yours!&mdash;From what motive?&mdash; From benevolence?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No: from &s;elf intere&s;t. He has an annuity on my life. The day I lo&s;e my exi&s;tence, he lo&s;es a hun|dred a year; and though he wouldn't give a doit to &s;ave me from perdition. I think he'd pay half-a-crown to pre|&s;erve his annuity.&mdash;Look&mdash;here he comes!&mdash;And now I think on't; &s;uppo&s;e I try to get our travelling expences out of him?&mdash;He is always enquiring after my health and&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I under&s;tand. I'll get out of the way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do Retire behind tho&s;e trees&mdash;Mum!&mdash;Ob|&s;erve.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Mandeville goes behind trees.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> REALIZE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So&mdash;I've drawn out my forces to the be&s;t advan|tage&mdash;Two of my officers are in ambu&s;h near the Ca&s;tle&mdash;two are reconnoitring on the London road&mdash;and two&mdash; Ha! Mr. Howard! How d'ye do, Mr. Howard?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hem!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Coughing, and fluffing his handkerchief into his mouth.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have you &s;een any thing of Mandeville?&mdash;I've two writs out again&s;t hin&mdash;one on my own account; the other on Sir Solomon's; and if you'll tell me where he is&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Howard coughs loudly]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Why, what's the matter with you? &mdash;That's an ugly cough.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ugly!&mdash;It's frightful!&mdash;it's&mdash;Hem!&mdash;Oh, Mr. Realize, I'm very ill!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ill!&mdash;You were very well ye&s;terday, and the day before, and every day &s;ince you came from your travels.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's it. I didn't mention it before, Mr. Re|alize, for fear of di&s;tre&s;&s;ing you; but, during my travels &mdash;Ough! ou! ou! <STAGE><HI>[Coughing violently]</HI></STAGE> I &s;lept in the Pontine mar&s;hes; and the pe&s;tiferous dews &s;o inflamed my lungs, that ever &s;ince&mdash;Hoop! oop! <STAGE><HI>[Coughing.]</HI></STAGE> I &s;hall die, that's certain.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="25" REF="25">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Die!&mdash;Impo&s;&s;ible!&mdash;Die!&mdash;I've an annuity on his life!&mdash;Oh! cur&s;e tho&s;e Pontine mar&s;hes!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>It's all Sir Solomon's fault. If he'd let me fol|low the doctor's advice, I &s;hould &s;ave my life, and you your annuity. But avarice, Mr. &mdash;Ava&mdash;Oop!&mdash;hem!&mdash;I'm a dead man!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You're not! Now, pray live! I'll take it as a fa|vour if you live!&mdash;My dear Mr. Howard, what did the doctor pre&s;cribe?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Change of air, and Bri&s;tol waters.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Bri&s;tol waters?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir: and becau&s;e I can't rai&s;e money to take me there&mdash;Oop!&mdash;becau&s;e Sir Solomon won't advance a few pounds&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'm to lo&s;e a hundred a year. Oh! the hard-hearted &s;avage! Why, I'd better give the money my&s;elf. I will. Here, Mr. Howard, <STAGE><HI>[Taking out a pur&s;e.]</HI></STAGE> I was always of a humane di&s;po&s;ition, and &s;o here's thirty&mdash;Hold though: Are you &s;ure the Bri&s;tol waters will cure you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Certain. The detergency of the atmo&s;phere; the ab&s;orbency of the chalybeate; the pondero&s;ity of&mdash;Hau!&mdash;au!&mdash;I'm convul&s;ed! Support me!&mdash;Lay hold of me!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[In his convul&s;ions, he lays hold of the hand in which Realize has the pur&s;e]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;So&mdash;Let me go!&mdash;I'm better now&mdash;Thank'ye.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Takes away his hand, and the pur&s;e with it.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Better&mdash;'Gad! no wonder at it. The do&s;e you've taken is more likely to do you good, than detergency, ab|&s;orbency, or all the doctors and apothecaries in Europe! However, a hundred per annum is worth thirty pounds, or the devil's in it! So keep it, and good bye to you. Hark'ye, though; if you &s;ee Mandeville, don't &s;ay I've placed bailiffs on the London road.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I won't.&mdash;Good bye. I hope I &s;hall mend, for your &s;ake, Mr. Realize.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I hope you will. But if you do not, if you find you grow wor&s;e, write me word you are coming home full of health and &s;pirits, and I'll go directly to Sir Solo|mon, talk of the goodne&s;s of your life, and &s;ell him the annuity at a premium! That will be puni&s;hing him for his
<PB N="26" REF="26">&s;tingine&s;s, and paying me for the do&s;e of phy&s;ic I've given you. Farewell! Keep your&s;elf warm, and &s;ucce&s;s to the Bri&s;tol waters! Oh! cur&s;e tho&s;e Pontine mar&s;hes!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! ble&s;s them! I &s;ay. Ha! ha! ha! I'm cured of my cough now&mdash;Hem! <STAGE><HI>[Clearing him&s;elf.]</HI></STAGE> Come forth, Mr. Mandeville <STAGE><HI>[Mandeville re-enters.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Come and congratulate your friend on the recovery of his health. Look&mdash;Will you go to Bri&s;tol?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No: to London.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not yet; there are enemies on the road. We mu&s;t wait till the pur&s;uit is over; and, as I know no &s;afer place than Cop&s;ley's cottage, let's return there in&s;tantly. Let us go &s;it and rail at the Governe&s;s and Albina.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Never. I mu&s;t &s;till think &s;he is my daughter, and hope the time may come when &s;he will imitate her mother's virtues. Oh, Howard! you &s;hould have known Amelia: &s;he had a heart as generous as your own&mdash;like you, &s;he gave up all for a di&s;tre&s;&s;ed&mdash;unhappy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay: no more melancholy, now, Mr. Mande|ville. How can a man talk of di&s;tre&s;s, when he &s;ees he can rai&s;e thirty pounds the moment he wants it? A &s;light cough and a &s;hort convul&s;ion will be at any time a Bank|note to us. So now for the cottage; and over a jug of old Cop&s;ley's October, let us drink "Confu&s;ion to our ene|mies and the Pontine mar&s;hes, and &s;ucce&s;s to our&s;elves and the Bri&s;tol waters!"</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Holding up a pur&s;e, and ex|eunt.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A forward Lan&s;cape.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ALBINA <HI>in the Uniform of a Li$$tonant of the Navy,</HI> Mrs. RIGID, <HI>and</HI> REALIZE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We won't detain you a moment, Mr. Stew|ard. Only &s;hew us the way to Cop&s;ley's cottage and you may return to your pur&s;uit of Mandeville. This young gentleman, Mr. Herbert&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Herbert! Pray is this one of the late Mrs. Man|deville's nephews?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am Sir. I am the fir&s;t co$$$$ of Mi&s;s A$$i$$, Sir
<PB N="27" REF="27">&mdash;of that much wronged and mo&s;t beautiful creature, Sir. I am lately come from &s;ea, and have been in &s;o many fiery engagements, that I don't know whether I am alive or dead, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Po! po! Non&s;en&s;e! <STAGE><HI>[Puts on his &s;pectacles, and looks clo&s;e at Albina.]</HI></STAGE> You been in fiery engagements! Pooh!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, come; Mr. Realize is too well ac|quainted with every part of the family to be impo&s;ed up|on; and therefore we may as well tru&s;t him at once. It is Albina! She has put on this di&s;gui&s;e, to detect Mr. How|ard in his love-affair with the Game keeper's daughter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, Sir; with that little coar&s;e, tann'd&mdash;&s;hew us the way, Sir&mdash;I know Mr. Howard is now at the cottage.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do you? That's very good. Love affair too!&mdash;Ha! ha! I wi&s;h you could prove your words.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e it would have &s;aved me thirty pounds. Why poor gentleman! he is not in a &s;tate to make love&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;the Pontine mar&s;hes have played the devil with his lungs, and he is gone to drink the Bri&s;tol waters.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Gone to Bri&s;tol! When?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now&mdash;this very moment!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Which way? How did he go?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How? Why, he went with my money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! This is all an impo&s;ition: all a contri|vance of Howard's to avoid detection. Lead on, Sir; I'm &s;ure his lungs were &s;ound enough two hours ago.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well! have it your own way&mdash;I only wi&s;h I was as &s;ure of keeping my annuity, as that you won't find him at the Cottage. No&mdash;and what's more to the purpo&s;e, that you find &s;omebody el&s;e there.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs, <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Some body el&s;e! Whom Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No le&s;s a gentleman than Sir Solomon Cynic! Not ten minutes ago I &s;aw him hovering about the &s;pot, like an old kite over a brood of chickens.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, the man's mad!&mdash;Sir Solomon make love! Shew us the way, I in&s;i&s;t, Sir. Come, child.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Dear! If, after all, the old woman-hater &s;hould turn out to be the real poacher!&mdash;If he &s;hould, Gover|ne&s;s! I'm &s;ure you won't any longer forbid me the fight of
<PB N="28" REF="28">Mr. Howard. 'Tis cruel to &s;por$ with the affections of a lover: and in the words of the old &s;ong, let me remind you&mdash;</P>
<STAGE>SONG.
<L>If 'tis joy to wound a lover,</L>
<L>How much more to give him ea&s;e!</L>
<L>When his pa&s;&s;ion we di&s;cover,</L>
<L>Oh! how plea&s;ing 'tis to plea&s;e! &amp;c.</L></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A Room in Cop&s;ley's Cottage&mdash;Birds of prey painted on the Wall&mdash;A Rece&s;s, with &s;everal Tru&s;&s;es of Straw in it&mdash;Before Rece&s;s, an old green Curtain, partly broken down&mdash;A Table and two Chairs&mdash;Ba&s;ket of Apples&mdash;Jug of Ale, and &s;mall Mug.</HEAD>
<STAGE>Sir SOLOMON <HI>di&s;covered kneeling to</HI> CICELY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh you lovelie&s;t of all creatures! When I railed at the &s;ex I did not know you&mdash;You have converted me! your charms have made me a pro&s;elyte, and here I &s;wear&mdash;here in this low, &s;ubmi&s;&s;ive, &s;uppliant&mdash;Wheugh! <STAGE><HI>[Whi&s;tling with pain.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;This is to be out of practice! My knees are &s;o unaccu&s;tomed to the office, that I believe I'd better get up while I'm able&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Ri&s;$s.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;So, come, I'll give you a toa&s;t, my little Cherub&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Goes to the table, and takes up a jug of ale]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Here's Cupid! victorious Cupid!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lord!&mdash;You're &s;o gallant. Sir Solomon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Gallant!&mdash;I have more requi&s;ites for a lover than any man &s;ince the days of Mark Antony. I can write &s;onnets, throw glances, talk non&s;en&s;e, tell lies, &s;ing, dance&mdash;No, hang it! I can't dance&mdash;if I could, I &s;houldn't be compelled to drink&mdash;" Confu&s;ion to all dancing-ma&s;|ters!"</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Drinking.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well; but your Honour! I hope my poor father will be re&s;tored to his &s;ituation&mdash;I am &s;o unhappy&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ee you are, and I know the cau&s;e&mdash;Take comfort&mdash;I'll give you love for love!&mdash;But how &s;hall we
<PB N="29" REF="29">meet?&mdash;How carry on our amour in a &s;nug, private, pa&s;|toral way?&mdash;How &s;hall I &s;teal to you unnoticed and un|&s;een?&mdash;And now I think on't&mdash;Zounds! I hope nobody's ob&s;erving us&mdash;if I &s;hould be found out!&mdash;if <HI>I</HI> &s;hould be detected in an intrigue?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>An intrigue, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hark'ye; to make all &s;afe, we'll go to London. There we may make a&s;&s;ignations without being $al$ed of or interrupted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic. [With anger.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes. There half the town are playing at the &s;ame game&mdash;But here in the country, if one gets a fly ki&s;s, the whole village is &s;ure to hear the &s;mack of it.&mdash;So Ma|rybone is the mark&mdash;a new hou&s;e and &s;mart liveries! a curricle and a pair of greys! a piano forte and a lap dog&mdash;and you &s;hall go by another name.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! &s;hall I change my name?&mdash;Oh, Sir!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Curt&s;ies very low.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure: you &s;hall no longer be called Ci|cely Cop&s;ley.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I be your wife!&mdash;Oh dear!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[with great joy.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My wife!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Shall I be Lady Cynic?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You Lady Cyn$$!&mdash;You my&mdash;Ha! ha! ha!&mdash;Why, my dear girl, you mi&s;conceive&mdash;I wi&s;h to in|trigue my&s;elf; I don't want to be the cau&s;e of intriguing in others&mdash;Marry you!&mdash;Lord help you&mdash;I wouldn't take &s;uch a liberty.&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[K$$$hing at the door.]</HI></STAGE> Hah! What&mdash;Who's here?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven know$&mdash;Perhaps my father, perhaps Mr. Howard, perhaps&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A dancing ma&s;ter!&mdash;Oh you &s;orcere&s;s, you've lured me here to $$pu&s;$ me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard. [With$$t.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hollo$! Cop&s;ley! Cicely!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Howard's voice! Mercy on me! If you don't get me off. I'll have your father hanged&mdash;I'll&mdash;Here&mdash;I'll go into this room.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stop, that's my chamber.&mdash;Here, Sir, go into that place <STAGE><HI>[pointing to the rece&s;s],</HI></STAGE> and I'll draw the curtain be|fore you.&mdash;Quick!&mdash;quick!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="30" REF="30">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This is my fir&s;t amour the&s;e twenty years: and if ever I come near a petticoat again, may Cupid fly away with me!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[He enters rece&s;s, and &s;its on a tru&s;s of &s;traw.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;So&mdash;draw the curtain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I can't&mdash;You &s;ee it's broken down, and&mdash;Dear! dear!&mdash;How &s;hall I fa&s;ten it?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Here&mdash;here!&mdash;My cane has a &s;word in it&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Draws the &s;word out of the cane, and gives it to Cicely]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;If there's a cranny in the wain&s;cot, run this through the cur|tain; if not, run it through my body.&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Cicely gets upon a chair and runs the &s;word through the curtain, which &s;upports it]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Oh woman! woman!&mdash;De&s;tructive, damnable, de|ceitful woman!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Sir Solomon is cencealed, and Cicely opens the door.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MANDEVILLE <HI>and</HI> HOWARD.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard. [Holding the door open, and looking out.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;Look out&mdash;look out, I tell you&mdash;'Tis Realize and the Governe&s;s; and by their coming this way, I fear you are di&s;covered&mdash;Hu&s;h!&mdash;ob&s;erve.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do; and &s;ee! the young naval officer is advanc|ing towards the cottage!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So he is!&mdash;We mu&s;t avoid him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Without.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;"The &s;tormy main, the wind and rain."&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[&s;inging.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, you chirruping &s;coundrel:&mdash;I tell you what&mdash;We had better &s;tep into this apartment, and let Ci|cely get rid of him&mdash;Mind, nobody is here, Cicely.&mdash;That, a naval officer!&mdash;Pooh!&mdash;Don't you &s;ee through his di&s;|gui&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Di&s;gui&s;e!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He's a bailiff! Can't you di&s;criminate between the navy and the law?&mdash;between a &s;ea officer and a &s;he|riff's officer?&mdash;I know by the ra&s;cal's impudent &s;wagger that he's a bailiff!&mdash;Here he comes!&mdash;Mum!&mdash;Retire.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[Exeunt at the oppo&s;ite door.]</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ALBINA <HI>in the Uniform.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [&s;pying and walking round the room.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>"The &s;tormy
<PB N="31" REF="31">main, the wind and rain!"&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[&s;inging.]</HI></STAGE> I don't &s;ee Mr. Howard!&mdash;"My ardent pa&s;&s;ion prove!"&mdash;He's con|cealed &s;omewhere, I &s;uppo&s;e.&mdash;"La&s;h'd to the helm"&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Goes up to the curtain]</HI></STAGE> He's here!&mdash;"Should &s;eas o'erwhelm."&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic. [Stopping her.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What do you want, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>"To think of thee, my love!"</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Trying to undraw the curtain.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic. [Pulling her away.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There's nobody there, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then they're here!&mdash;"And think of thee, my love!"&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Goes towards the door.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Perhaps, after all, he is really gone to Bri&s;tol; and his lungs are &s;o much out of order. <STAGE><HI>[Trying to open the door, and finding it locked.]</HI></STAGE> Lock'd! Where's the key?&mdash;Oh! oh! <STAGE><HI>[Stoops down.]</HI></STAGE> I &s;ee him through the key-hole!&mdash;Oh! you barbarian! <STAGE><HI>[Cicely tries to pull her away.]</HI></STAGE> If you touch me, you little vulgar thing, I'll cut you into atoms!&mdash;I &s;ee you, Mr. Howard.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Hollaing through the key-hole.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, I be&s;eech you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Trying to pull the door open.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! if I could but get at him!&mdash;Come out, Sir; or I'll pull the door.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Shaking it violently.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HOWARD.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, Sir! What do you want, Sir?&mdash;What have you to &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Say, Sir! I'm glad your lungs are better.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard. [Standing before the door.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My lungs!&mdash;Hark'ye, Sir; if you want Mr. Mandeville&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I want you, and only you, Sir!&mdash;My name is Herbert&mdash;I am fir&s;t cou&s;in to Albina; and if you don't in&s;tantly fall on your knees, and a&s;k pardon for the in&s;ults you have put upon her, I'll make you a companion for that wild goo&s;e&mdash;I'll run you through the body, and pin you again&s;t the wall&mdash;'Slife! now I look at you, I wonder what &s;he could &s;ee in your ugly face to be &s;o fond of you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'm glad it's not a bailiff, however. <STAGE><HI>[A&s;ide.]</HI></STAGE> Sir, if you are that lady's cou&s;in, I mu&s;t inform you &s;he isn't worth my pity, or your re&s;entment. She is neither
<PB N="32" REF="32">faithful to her lover, nor affectionate to her father. In &s;hort, Sir, I thought her a child of nature, and I found her a Becky.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>A Becky!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: a Becky, Sir!&mdash;And till &s;he reforms her conduct, not all the fighting men in Europe &s;hall make me alter mine. This is my determination, and &s;o you may tell her, good Captain Bobadil.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Bobadil!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: Bobadil may tell Becky&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Draw, Sir!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Pulls out her &s;word]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hold, I intreat you&mdash;What is the cau&s;e?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You&mdash;Come, Sir!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Flouri&s;hing her &s;word.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>His love for you is the cau&s;e. Sir Solomon told me of his fal&s;hood, and now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Solomon told you?&mdash;Oh! ba&s;e, &s;landerous man!&mdash;Love never brought Mr. Howard to our cottage. No: He came from a far better motive&mdash;to bring mo|ney to my father&mdash;to relieve the di&s;tre&s;&s;es of his family: and, with gratitude I &s;peak it, he has already &s;aved us from ruin.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes: but for him we &s;hould have peri&s;hed; and, as a proof I wasn't the object of his affections, often and often have I heard him &s;ay, that Mi&s;s Albina, was the girl of his heart, and that he never would or could love any other.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Smiling.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! did you &s;ay this, Mr. Howard?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You have heard my determination. I will not be tea&s;ed with interrogatories.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Going up to him.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay: don't be &s;o ha&s;ty, Mr. Howard. Con&s;ider, if Sir Solomon has deceived me&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis now too late, Sir.&mdash;Your vi&s;it: her partiality for her perfidious governe&s;s; and her neglect of a too liberal parent, are all&mdash;all &s;o di&s;graceful, that, if ever I love again, depend on't Albina won't be the object.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Sharply.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She won't!&mdash;Who will then, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye: who, Sir?&mdash;Will this little, coar&s;e, in|&s;en&s;ible pea&s;ant?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="33" REF="33">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>In&s;en&s;ible! Look him in the face, Cicely <STAGE><HI>[ta|king her hand]:</HI></STAGE> tell him you would die to &s;erve your fa|ther; and a&s;k him if Albina would &s;hed a tear to &s;ave hers.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He pre&s;&s;es her hand!&mdash;Let it go, Sir?&mdash;If you value your life, take away your hand, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why? She de&s;erves it as much as your cou&s;in!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I can't bear it! Take it away! Then &s;ay your pray|ers, for you hav'n't a moment to live!&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[poking at him with her &s;word.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Keep off, Sir! You &s;ee I've no arms.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No arms! That's a poor eva&s;ion, coward!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Coward! Oh, that I could find a weapon! Is there no poker&mdash;no knife&mdash;no&mdash;Ha! what do I &s;ee?&mdash;A &s;word! Now, villain!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hear me, Sir! Don't touch it, for Heaven's &s;ake!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hear her, Sir! Don't touch it, for Heaven's &s;ake!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Thus I expo&s;e folly and deception!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Pulls out the Sword that &s;upports the curtain; it falls, and Sir Solomon is di&s;covered fitting on one tru&s;s of &s;traw, with others around him.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Expo&s;e folly and deception, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He's innocent! he's innocent! Oh! Howard!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What the old woman-hater turned poacher! Ha! ha! ha!&mdash;Why, uncle!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, man of &s;traw! ha! ha! ha! Look, how the old fox &s;quats in the &s;tubble!&mdash;Come! <STAGE><HI>[handing him out]</HI></STAGE> What have you to &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing. I'll go home, and read Paradi&s;e Lo&s;t!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And cur&s;e Cupid and Mark Antony. And now, Sir! <STAGE><HI>[to Albina]</HI></STAGE> What have you to &s;ay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That I &s;incerely a&s;k your pardon: that I &s;ee you have been &s;landered, cruelly &s;landered! And if Albina was before partial to you, &s;he &s;hall now e&s;teem you more than ever. Will you forgive me, Sir? I'll tell her all that has pa&s;&s;ed&mdash;every thing.&mdash;No, I won't tell her you called her Becky. You don't call her Becky now, do you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid. [Without.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mr. Herbert! Mr. Herbert!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You hear I'm called Sir. Do we part friends?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>We do: I'm &s;atisfied.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="34" REF="34">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And I needn't m$$tion Becky?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No! no!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then let my Governe&s;s &s;ay what &s;he will, How|ard is the hu&s;band for Albina! <STAGE><HI>[a&s;ide]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Farewell, Sir! we &s;hall meet again. Cicely, there's money for you. And, Sir Solomon, the next time a game keeper catches one of your hares, don't &s;nare one of his daughters, and make him &s;tarve for it into the bargain! And al&s;o, to cover your own poaching practices, don't &s;lander an innocent Gentle|man. If you do, I'll chain you to your bed of &s;traw, de|pend on't. Adieu! Mr. Howard!</P>
<Q><L>"La&s;h'd to the helm, &s;hould &s;eas o'erwhelm,</L>
<L>"I'll think on thee, my Love."</L></Q>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir, you may &s;mile, and chuckle, and triumph; but I'll be rev$$ged on you and Mr. Mandeville yet. I know he is in that room. I &s;aw him &s;n$$k in there; and while $eali$$ &s;pe$$es him, Veritas &s;hall &s;ecure A$$i$$$.&mdash;I'll overtake Mrs. Rigid&mdash;the $$$$c$ &s;hall take place this $$$y night; and th$$, Sir&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay; why &s;hould you fret? Upon my &s;oul, I think you're a very lucky f$llow. If you had not been in the &s;traw, &s;omebody el&s;e $ight! You under&s;tand?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir. <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do; and I've pl$g$$ enough with nephews, without wi&s;hing for children $word$ torment me. Let me go&mdash;let me f$llow Mrs. Rigid <STAGE><HI>[Cicely &s;tops him.]</HI></STAGE> One of the way, Jilt! S$$$$je&s;s! Je$$bel! or, to &s;um up all in one empha|tic word&mdash;Out of the way, Woman!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand. [p$$ping.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is the coa&s;t clear?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard. [opens the door, and enter Mandeville.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>&mdash;Well! have you heard what has p$&s;&s;ed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand!</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I have. I perceive this is no longer a place of &s;afety&punc; and what's wor&s;e, that Albina's marriage is to take place this very night! Is there no way to break it off? Con&s;ider, for her own &s;ake, for yours, for $ine, we &s;hould prevent it, if we can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Prevent it! How?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have you no influence ever the Tutor? Has he no &s;en&s;e of honour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, if it be true, that "wine draws forth the natural di&s;po&s;ition of the heart," Veritas has &s;till &s;ome
<PB N="35" REF="35">virtue; for over a bottle I've &s;een him di&s;play mo&s;t ex|cellent qualities. I'll go to him; I'll try to delay, if not break off, the marriage! In the mean time, you &s;hall take refuge in the uninhabited part of the Ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why there?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e it is &s;uppo&s;ed to be haunted; and Rea|lize and his followers won't come their, for fear of &s;eeing the Devil before there time, you know. Come! while I go to the Tutor, Cicely &s;hall &s;hew you the place. Oh, you little gleaner! If I had known that &s;traw contained &s;uch weighty heads of corn among&s;t it, how I would have thre&s;h'd it! I'd have laid my flail about its ears, till I had beat every grain of prejudice out of it, and made the old woman hater acknowledge,</P>
<L>That, let us rail at women, &s;corn, and flout them.</L>
<L>We may live with, but cannot live without them.</L>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<TRAILER>END OF ACT III.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<DIV2 N="4" TYPE="act">
<PB N="36" REF="36">
<HEAD>ACT IV.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A modern Apartment in the Ca&s;tle.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HOWARD <HI>and</HI> VERITAS.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>HOWARD.</SPEAKER>
<P>WHAT! Veritas turned flincher! Come, one more bottle, my boy!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I tell you, I've had enough. I'm going to be mar|ried: and would you have me get drunk before the cere|mony's performed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure: would a man marry in his &s;ober &s;en&s;es? Come, though we're rivals, don't let us be ene|mies; though you've cut me out with Albina, I bear you no ill will&mdash;Do let us part friends. Come, one more bot|tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I would, but you know my failing, George: wine makes me &s;o cruelly &s;entimental; it overflows my heart with &s;ympathy, runs out of my eyes in &s;treams of &s;en&s;ibi|lity; and when I'm no longer my&s;elf, I'm &s;o moral, and &s;o hone&s;t.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So you are. When you're not your&s;elf, you're a damn'd good &s;ort of fellow!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Granted: I'm never &s;o upright in my conduct, as when I can't &s;tand on my legs! Then wine always makes me &s;peak truth; and if I don't take care, I &s;hall tell you at this moment, that I am a &s;coundre!&mdash;that the Governe&s;s is another&mdash;and that Albina&mdash;Good night, George. After the wedding's over, I'll reform, and be a &s;ix-bottle man!&mdash;But now, &s;pare and pity me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Pity you! Why?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becau&s;e I'm going to behave like a villain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You're not: I'll prevent you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis too late&mdash;the dark de$d is on the ev$ of exe|cution!&mdash;Albina's locked up in the old Baron's chamber&mdash;the Lawyer has prepared the &s;$$$l$ment&mdash;the Par&s;on has
<PB N="37" REF="37">got the licence, and&mdash;Damnation! what am I about? I &s;hall confe&s;s every thing&mdash;Good night!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Here's my Uncle and the Governe&s;s! What can it all mean? Look ye, Veritas, if &s;ome new act of villainy is in perpetration, do you think I'll &s;uffer my old fellow traveller to be concerned in it? No: I have too much regard for your honour; and I know you are &s;o apt to repent&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am; and the wine converts me already. I'm a fair penitent; and &s;o let's go and drink whole oceans&mdash;and yet, George, I don't like to lo&s;e Albina: &s;he is the only woman I &s;hall ever love.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Non&s;en&s;e! you're only drunk one bottle, and therefore there's only one Albina. Drink another, and there'll be a thou&s;and Albinas! Come along, my fine fel|low; and if wine will make you moral, damme but you &s;hall drink hone&s;ty by hog&s;heads!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir SOLOMON <HI>and</HI> Mrs. RIGID.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't tell me, Sir Solomon! Is &s;he to be my mi&s;tre&s;s, or am I to be hers? Talk of marrying How|ard, and refu&s;ing Veritas, only becau&s;e you were uncur|tain'd at the Gamekeeper's cottage! I wi&s;h you had never gone there, with all my heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So do I, with all my &s;oul! But you mi&s;conceive: I don't oppo&s;e the marriage; I only object to the manner of of wooing. I don't like u&s;ing force.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why not, Sir? If entreaty fail, why &s;houldn't force be employed? Isn't it as much her intere&s;t to marry a man of honour, as it is my duty to prevent her being united to a profligate?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That's true.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And hasn't Mr. Veritas both your promi&s;e and mine; and would it be honourable to break our word with him? No: I &s;ay once for all, &s;he &s;hall be his wife, this very night! She is now locked up in the Baron's cham|ber; and if &s;he refu&s;es, there &s;he &s;hall be impri&s;oned till &s;he complies. She &s;hall have no companions but gho&s;ts and &s;pectres&mdash;no food but bread and water&mdash;no bed but &s;traw.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Straw!&mdash;There I mu&s;t intercede for her: that's &s;o b$d a re&s;ting place, that the very thought of it will &s;poil
<PB N="38" REF="38">my night's &s;leep, to a certainty!&mdash;However, there is much rea&s;on in what you &s;ay; and if &s;he won't &s;elect a good hu&s;band, we mu&s;t choo&s;e one for her!&mdash;So if the Par|&s;on, the Lawyer, and the Tutor are ready, I'll join the party, and we'll proceed to the Baron's chamber in a body.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Spoke like your&s;elf, Sir Solomon!&mdash;Stay&mdash;wait here a moment, while I go and prepare them. And if &s;he dare be refractory&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Refractory!&mdash;Why a tutor and a governe&s;s would alone terrify a girl of her age; but backed by a Lawyer and a Par&s;on&mdash;Gad! I &s;hould like to &s;ee any body &s;tand up again&s;t &s;o formidable a quartetto! <STAGE><HI>[Exit Mrs. Rigid.]</HI></STAGE> I am glad of this!&mdash;Now Howard will lo&s;e Albina, Mande|ville will lo&s;e the e&s;tate, and the Tutor will be rewarded for his integrity and &s;obriety.&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Noi&s;e without.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Bravo! here they come, and all in high &s;pirits for the enterprize.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HOWARD <HI>and</HI> VERITAS <HI>arm in arm, drunk.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come along, Pupil&mdash;Come along, Hone&s;ty!&mdash;Uncle! how are you, Uncle?&mdash;Give me leave to introduce you&mdash;a fair penitent!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, how did you get into the Ca&s;tle? Who invited you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My pupil here. Speak, &s;uffering faint!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Out of the way, Sir&mdash;I'll hold no conver&s;ation with drunkards and buffoons&mdash;I'll talk to men of &s;en&s;e and gravity.&mdash;Veritas, give me your hand.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Granted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And now let me give it to Albina.&mdash;Puppy, will you be eye-witne&s;s to the marriage?&mdash;Will you be|hold this worthy man take po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of your idol and ten thou&s;and a-year?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Look'ye, King Solomon&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, mind, King Solomon.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If I thought Albina loved me, I'm &s;o brimful of benevolence, that I'd take her without a guinea; but to marry her again&s;t her inclinations!&mdash;to u&s;e force&mdash;to&mdash;I tell you it's a damned ra&s;cally tran&s;action. And if you and the Governe&s;s would get as drunk as I am, you'd be as much a&s;hamed of it as I am!&mdash;So drink, drink and reform!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I drink!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why not, Uncle?&mdash;There's as much virtue in
<PB N="39" REF="39">wine as in women! <STAGE><HI>[Sir Solomon holds up his cane to &s;trike him&mdash;Veritas interpo&s;es.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;What! have you not had enough of that cane? that pinner-up of old curtains! Pooh! I don't value it a &s;traw!&mdash;not a &s;traw! So come, Pupil; you've made your &s;peech. And now let's adjourn to the inn, and drink more draughts of morality.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. RIGID.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>All's ready&mdash;all's prepared, Sir Solomon!&mdash;Howard here!&mdash;Why, cou&s;in!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Going up to Veritas.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard. [Stopping her.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Softly, Doctor Bu&s;by&mdash;You won't let me &s;peak to your pupil, therefore you mu&s;t not talk to mine. He's a good boy, and you may corrupt him. Keep off.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>They're both Intoxicated!&mdash;Heaven defend me!&mdash;Why, Veritas, are not you a&s;hamed?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not a bit.&mdash;There's &s;ome apology for drunken ho|ne&s;ty&mdash;but none for &s;ober villainy. So drink, drink and reform!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stick to your bottle, Doctor.&mdash;'In vino Ve|ritas!'</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Sings.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, George.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come!&mdash;Why would you leave me at this moment?&mdash;now, when Albina is locked up&mdash;when the Lawyer and the Clergyman are waiting?&mdash;What &s;hall I do?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Do? Tell the two black gentlemen to &s;trike out the name of Veritas in their papers&mdash;&s;ub&s;titute mine in its place, and I'll return and marry Albina in half an hour!&mdash;No, I won't marry her. Till &s;he's a good daugh|ter, &s;he &s;han't have a good hu&s;band!&mdash;So come, my boy. Now for the inn!&mdash;I &s;ay though, isn't it a long way?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Long! No; when a man's drunk, it isn't the length.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>True; it's the width. Farewell, mo&s;t amiable, mo&s;t Platonic pair!&mdash;"To wine I flew to ea&s;e the pain!"&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[B$$h &s;inging.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Ver.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell, King Solomon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Good b'ye, Doctor Bu&s;by!&mdash;"To wine I flew," &amp;c.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit with Veritas.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Amazing! What does it mean, Sir Solo|mon? Has Howard corrupted him?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He has; and now I'm decided: they &s;hall nei|ther of them enter my doors again; and as for Mandeville, I'll make an example of him directly. I have traced him
<PB N="40" REF="40">from the cottage to the back part of the Ca&s;tle: he is now concealed among&s;t the ruins; and I'll go order Realize to lay hold of him this very moment. In the interim, do you take care of Albina.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, &s;he's very &s;afe. I have placed Deborah, a &s;teady old &s;ervant, as a guard over her; and the haunt|ed chamber &s;hall be her abode till we find a new hu&s;band for her. Good night, Sir Solomon!&mdash;I couldn't have thought that Mr. Veritas would have turned out &s;uch a&mdash;.But it's a &s;trange world; and we have lived &s;o long in it, that nothing ought now to perplex or &s;urpri&s;e us.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing ever &s;urpri&s;es me; and &s;uch are the changes of this whirl-about life, that though your &s;y&s;tem is Platonic love, and mine no love at all, yet I &s;houldn't be a&s;toni&s;hed if we were to become man and wife, and be as happy a couple, Mrs. Rigid, as&mdash;No, hang it! That would &s;urpri&s;e me, indeed!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt &s;everally.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;An old Gothic Chamber, with Doors at each $ing&mdash;in the Flat another Door&mdash;Over it is the Portrait of a Man in Armour&mdash;A State Bed.</HEAD>
<STAGE>ALBINA <HI>(&s;till in the Lieutenant's Uniform) di&s;covered writing</HI>&mdash;DEBORAH <HI>waiting.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Deborah!&mdash;Do take your hand from the table, Deborah: you &s;hake it &s;o I can't go on with my letter. "Dear Mr. Howard."&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>Writing.</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Lord, Mi&s;s! Isn't it midnight? and ar'n't we alone in a haunted chamber?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Haunted! Fooli&s;h non&s;en&s;e! I &s;uppo&s;e you've been prying into tho&s;e new romances the Governe&s;s bought for me&mdash;all about abbeys, &s;keletons, ru&s;ty daggers, fat monks, and fainting nuns. Pooh! It's all very well to frighten children; but for &s;uch grown-up mi&s;&s;es as you and I, Deborah&mdash;Oh, we're not afraid of the dead&mdash;no|thing but the living frightens us. So &s;it fa&s;t in your chair.&mdash;And now for the letter&mdash;"Dear Mr. Howard&mdash;They have locked me up in an uninhabited part of the Ca&s;|tle, and placed an old ma&s;tiff over me."</P>
<STAGE><HI>[The Ca&s;tle clock &s;trikes one.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There&mdash;he's coming!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who's coming?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="41" REF="41">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Baron&mdash;the Baron!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What Baron?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why, in days of yore an old Norman Baron was murdered in that bed; and ever &s;ince, when the Ca&s;tle clock &s;trikes one, that door is &s;ure to open, <STAGE><HI>[pointing to it]</HI></STAGE> and in he &s;talks in black armour.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Does he indeed?&mdash;Well! I &s;hall be very glad to &s;ee him; and, that we may have a full view of him, do &s;nuff the candles.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Snuff the candles, Mi&s;s?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ave: Let's &s;ee what he's made of, Deborah.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb. [In her fright &s;nuffs out one of the candles.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aw the picture &s;hake; and that's a &s;ure &s;ign the Baron is ap|proaching.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So it is. I'll frighten her away if I can. <STAGE><HI>[A&s;ide.]</HI></STAGE> Hark! Don't you hear the rattling of armour?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And the clanking of chains; and the &s;creech owl; and the ravens; and the cats; and the mice? And don't you hear me, Deborah?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do. Oh, Lord! the Governe&s;s may come and watch you her&s;elf. I won't &s;tay to be hacked to pieces.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! The door opens; and there he is, as black as Beelzebub. Oh, dear, my courage fails me! Go to him. Deborah! and while he makes mince-meat of you, I &s;hall have time to run away. Pray do, Deborah.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not I! Heaven protect you!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exit, frightened.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ha! ha! ha! What an old coward it is! Now, nothing ever makes me tremble&mdash;nothing! Oh yes: the very thought of Howard makes me &s;o nervous&mdash;Heigho!&mdash;I'll proceed with the letter: <STAGE><HI>[Sits and writes.]</HI></STAGE> "and "placed an old ma&s;tiff over me,"&mdash;a pretty ma&s;tiff in|deed!&mdash; <Q>becau&s;e I won't marry the Tutor. But I am &startq;a girl of &s;uch pride, &s;uch &s;pirit, &s;uch fortitude, Mr. &endq;Howard,</Q><STAGE><HI>[The report of a pi&s;tol is heard.]</HI></STAGE> What's that? A pi&s;tol at this time of night, and &s;o near me! Lord! It's very alarming! Who can it be? Oh, it's the poochers $$$|ing at the game! P&s;ha! What a fool I was! Hem!" <STAGE><HI>[Sits and writes]</HI></STAGE><Q>I am a girl of &s;uch pride, &s;uch &s;pirit, &s;uch &startq;&endq;forti&mdash;</Q><STAGE><HI>[Noi&s;e of forcing open a door]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Well!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>Noi&s;e again.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Somebody's forcing the door! He's com|ing! The $$row's coming! <STAGE><HI>[Noi&s;e again.]</HI></STAGE> Oh dear! I'll
<PB N="42" REF="42">run away! <STAGE><HI>[Tries to open the door Deborah went out at, but finds it fa&s;tened]</HI></STAGE> Oh, &s;he has locked me in! Deborah! De|borah!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Runs and hides her&s;elf behind the bed]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[The door is bur&s;t open, and Mandeville enters with a pi&s;tol in his hand.]</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Life isn't worth the &s;truggle! Howard hadn't left me an hour among&s;t the ruins of the Ca&s;tle, when Realize and his followers came up with me; I remon&s;trated in vain, They &s;eized me; and feeing no other mode of extricating my&s;elf, I fired my pi&s;tol in the air, and the cowards vani&s;h|ed.&mdash;Here, perhaps, I may re&s;t in &s;afety. <STAGE><HI>[Sits down, and puts the pi&s;tol on the table.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;How! a light! I thought this part of the Ca&s;tle had been uninhabited! Sure nobody ob|&s;erves me! Ha! the curtain moves! One of the villains has pur&s;ued me! Is there to be no period to their per&s;e|cution? <STAGE><HI>[Pulls forth Albina]</HI></STAGE> Mark me, Sir. Return to the agent who employed you. Begone directly, or this pi&s;tol&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh Lord! Deborah! Deborah!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No noi&s;e! Begone this in&s;tant! <STAGE><HI>[Albina retires up.]</HI></STAGE> Stop. Come back. You may betray me to your cur&s;t a&s;&s;o|ciates: therefore remain. Sit down. <STAGE><HI>[Forces her into a chair.]</HI></STAGE> Stir not&mdash;look not&mdash;breathe not!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I won't. Deborah!&mdash;Debo&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! Or by Heaven!&mdash;Stay. Sure I &s;hould know that face. Speak&mdash;Do you not recollect me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No. But I &s;hall never forget you.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis the youth who came to the Cottage! 'Tis Herbert; and no doubt is on a vi&s;it to his cou&s;in. Cur&s;t infatuation! I'm doomed to be a torment. Sir, I've been mi&s;taken; and know too well the pangs of apprehen&s;ion, to wi&s;h to inflict them on others. Pray, pray pardon me!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Taking her hand.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>True fle&s;h and blood, I declare. I'm better now I may breathe again, I &s;uppo&s;e. Ooh! ooh! <STAGE><HI>Breathing vi|olently.</HI></STAGE> So, you're not an apparition then&mdash;you're only a robber?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Robber! Sir, I <HI>have</HI> been&mdash;Well, well! it con|cerns not you; el&s;e I could tell you that the &s;teward of this man&s;ion, this reptile Realize, who was about to make a pri&s;oner of me, and to who&s;e per&s;ecution you owe my pre|&s;ent intru&s;ion. Oh! in the lifetime of his ma&s;ter, the late too un&s;u&s;picious Mr. Mandeville, he would not&mdash;no, he
<PB N="43" REF="43">dared not e'en have frowned upon me. But I have done; I've already been the cau&s;e of much unea&s;ine&s;s to you&mdash;Therefore, good night!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stay, I mu&s;t hear more. Did you know Mr. Man|deville, Sir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Know him!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why are you &s;o agitated, Sir? If you knew him, perhaps you al&s;o know his unhappy &s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do indeed! And if I dare reveal to you&mdash;But I mu&s;t not tru&s;t to you&mdash;you are a friend of the Go|verne&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am: but I am al&s;o. a friend to the unfortunate. Come, you had better tru&s;t me&mdash;I have great influence over. Albina; and &s;ince you are the friend of Mr. Mandeville, I'll per&s;uade her to &s;atisfy this &s;teward&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Mandeville &s;hakes his head]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Nay, if you think &s;he has not a compa&s;|&s;ionate heart, you don't know her&mdash;indeed, you do not!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>She ought to be compa&s;&s;ionate. Her mother had a heart overflowing with benevolence, and her father&mdash;But he&mdash;he is forgotten&mdash;and de&s;erted.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Poor man! I often think of him&mdash;often &s;hed tears over his misfortunes. Where is he? Might I behold him!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Mandeville weeps.]</HI></STAGE> Nay, if you knew all, perhaps I have more cau&s;e to weep than you have.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You cut me to the &s;oul. I can't &s;upport it. Let me begone.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real. [Without.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This way&mdash;the ra&s;cal's this way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My per&s;ecutor again! What's to be done?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stay where you are; it's his turn now.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> REALIZE <HI>and two Servants.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There he is&mdash;&s;eize him&mdash;&s;ecure him, while I go for officers of ju&s;tice. You'll pop at us like &s;o many partridges, will you? <STAGE><HI>[Servants hold Mandeville.]</HI></STAGE> Keep him right; and now I may &s;afely &s;ay my troubles are at an end&punc;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Meeting him.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Rather &s;ay, your troubles are going to begin. Unhand that gentleman; let him go, I in&s;i&s;t. <STAGE><HI>[Servants leave Mandeville]</HI></STAGE> And now, Mr. Steward, a word in private if you plea&s;e. <STAGE><HI>[Mandeville retires up.]</HI></STAGE> You recol|lect me?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure I do.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="44" REF="44">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then hear me, Sir; I'll pay what he owes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You pay?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes, I'll pay. Can't you under&s;tand me? Go, Sir; and for the future don't di&s;grace your employers by acts of cruelty and oppre&s;&s;ion.&mdash;Why ar'n't you gone?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Um! Before I obey the young lady, I mu&s;t have orders from the old one. You'll excu&s;e me; but you're not your own mi&s;tre&s;s, you know, my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No. But I'm yours, you know, my dear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You're not. The Governe&s;s is my mi&s;tre&s;s. Pooh! You've no will of your own.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No! But I've a will of my grandfather's and if you don't in&s;tantly relea&s;e this Gentleman, I'll di&s;charge you from being my Steward&mdash;my Steward! Do you hear that, Sir? What does he owe?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why he owes me and Sir Solomon above fourteen hundred pounds; and do you think either of us will be content with the &s;ecurity of a minor? No, no; we'll have the money down.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So you &s;hall. Take it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Take it! Where?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Out of my grandfather's money.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! He didn't leave &s;o much ca&s;h behind him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Didn't he? Then he le&s;t hou&s;es, lands and woods. So go. Sir! Go cut down a wood directly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Cut down a wood!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, Sir. And if that won't rai&s;e the &s;um, cut dows another, and another. It will improve the pro&s;pect, and gratity Albina with the fine&s;t view in the world&mdash;that of &s;eeing an unfortunate man made happy.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Turning to Mandeville and taking his hand.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Here's a promi&s;ing young heire&s;s! Without the aid of a fa&s;hionable hu&s;band, &s;he'll lay wa&s;te more wood in an hour than her grandfather planted in his life time.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! not gone yet? I'm out of all patience. <STAGE><HI>[Takes up the pi&s;tol.]</HI></STAGE> Go, Sir. Begin lopping and chopping with your own hands, or this pi&s;tol&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What a devil it is! Come, William&mdash;Come Gre|gory. We'll go and &s;end the Governe&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What's that you &s;ay, Sir? Mind me! If you repeat one &s;yllable of what has pa&s;&s;ed, this pi&s;tol &s;hall prove more &s;ural to you than the Pontine mar&s;hes. It &s;hall make
<PB N="45" REF="45">as large a hole in your lungs, as the Bri&s;tol waters have in your pocket. Go, dotard. Quick! quick! <STAGE><HI>[Follows Rea|lize and Servants to the door with the pi&s;tol, and forces them out.]</HI></STAGE> So between &s;words and pi&s;tols I've had a pretty hot day of it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>How am I to thank you, Sir? Till now, I had but one friend&mdash;one only friend; and he, in poverty has proved &s;o generous. Oh! if you knew&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I wi&s;h I did know him, Sir. Whoever he is, if he has been kind to you, I'm &s;ure I &s;hall e&s;teem him. Come, though you won't mention your own name, you may tru&s;t me with his, who is your friend?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Howard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Howard! Has he&mdash;has Mr. Howard been kind to you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He has been my companion, my benefactor! He has di&s;plea&s;ed his family to a&s;&s;i&s;t me; and, what afflicts me more than all, on my account, I fear, he has offended the lady he mo&s;t loves.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed! And pray, who&mdash;Not that it's any af|fair of mine&mdash;But pray, who is the lady he mo&s;t loves?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who &s;hould it be but Albina? His hand, his heart, his life is at her di&s;po&s;al.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>His life! She mu&s;tn't let him die then. Tell him &s;o, Mr&mdash;Dear! I wi&s;h I knew your name. You &s;ay you are the friend of Mr. Mandeville&mdash;the friend of Mr. Howard! Can't you confide in me? <STAGE><HI>[Noi&s;e of unlocking the doer.]</HI></STAGE> Somebody's coming! The Steward has betraved us! What &s;hall we do? I'll &s;tand before, and hide you.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Places her&s;elf before Mandeville.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DEBORAH.</STAGE>
<P>Well. Deborah, what do you want?</P>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Steward has been with Mrs. Rigid. She is &s;uddenly taken ill; and de&s;ires I'll bring you to her own room directly. Why, what's that? Somebody is behind you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h! It's the Baron!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The Baron!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't be frightened!&mdash;He &s;peaks highly of you; and, though I told him it was impo&s;&s;ible, he &s;wears he'll make an angel of you.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="46" REF="46">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't&mdash;Pray don't let him.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well! He &s;ha'n't&mdash;he &s;ha'n't make an angel of you. Turn your back, and I'll lay him&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Deberah turns round.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;You &s;ee, I mu&s;t leave you at pre&s;ent. <STAGE><HI>[To Mande|vills.]</HI></STAGE> But as I cannot re&s;t till I know more of your &s;tory, don't leave the Ca&s;tle, I entreat you. Go into that room; and, that nobody may mole&s;t you, allow me to lock you in; and, when I return&mdash;Will you tru&s;t me when I re|turn?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mo&s;t readily.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Good night!&mdash;Nay: what have you to thank me for? Realize meant to make you his pri&s;oner; and now I've made you mine&mdash;that's all the difference&punc; Adieu! <STAGE><HI>[Mandeville &s;hakes hands with her, and exit at the do$r.&mdash;Al|bina locks it, and puts the key in her pocket.]</HI></STAGE> Deborah I He's gone Deborah!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Hitting Deborah on the bach, who trembles violently.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Is he? Which may did he go?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Through the key-hole; and now we'll go too.&mdash;Poor gentleman! I'll return to him as &s;oon as I can; for I &s;eal intere&s;ted for him beyond de&s;cription&mdash;Lond on&mdash;I'll follow thee! And oh, Mr. Howard! My dear Mr. Howard! Your friend&s;hip for him, and love for me, prove you to be a man of &s;uch ta&s;te and di&s;crimination, that, if you don't forgive me, and make me your wife&mdash;why, I'll live and die&mdash;a bachelor!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
<TRAILER>AND OF ACT IV.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
<PB N="47" REF="47">
<DIV2 N="5" TYPE="act">
<HEAD>ACT V.</HEAD>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;A Garden.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ALBINA <HI>in her own Dre&s;s.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>ALBINA.</SPEAKER>
<P>I CAN neither &s;it, &s;tand, nor walk. I can only bite my fingers, beat the devil's tattoo, and &s;ing broken &s;tanzas of de&s;paiting &s;ongs. "Ah, well-a-day&mdash;Ah, lack-a-day!" Dear! Now I only a&s;k if my Governe&s;s oughtn't to be a&s;hamed of her&s;elf? Without giving any rea&s;on, &s;he has ordered me to pack up, to &s;et out for Dover, and leave the Ca&s;tle and Mr. Howard for ever. I begin to hate her, that's what I do.&mdash;Sir Solomon too&mdash;I hate him! I hate all old people. I wi&s;h they'd go to heaven, and leave us young ones to manage the world by our&s;elves.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> DEBORAH.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s, Mi&s;s, the earringe is at the door&mdash;the po&s;|tillions are mounting, the hor&s;es are prancing, and Mrs. Rigid is out of all patience.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, I'm coming!&mdash;Deborah, what is the rea&s;on?&mdash;Nay, don't turn your back upon me&mdash;don't take, me for the Baron, Deborah!&mdash;Why are we to leave the Ca&s;tle &s;o unexpectedly?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Deb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I don't know; but I believe its all owing to what the Steward told her. Come, be quick&mdash;See now!&mdash;Here's Sir Solomon come to fetch you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir SOLOMON&mdash;<HI>[a letter in his hand.]</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Solomon, I know what you're come for. You mean to force me away from the Ca&s;tle.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I force you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I never di&s;obeyed my Governe&s;s in all my life&mdash;but now&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sel.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis high time to begin, I think.&mdash;Go, Madam, <STAGE><HI>[to Deb.]</HI></STAGE> tell Mrs. Rigid, Albins &s;ha'n't go to Dover.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not go to Dover?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No! You &s;ha'n't &s;tir from your own hou&s;e; or, if you do, it &s;hall only be to mine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! Will you &s;tand up for me, Sir Solomon?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="48" REF="48">
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure I will.&mdash;This letter has opened my eyes&mdash;it proves the Governe&s;s to be the wor&s;t of hy|pocrites; and therefore from this hour you &s;hall be your own mi&s;tre&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>School's up! School's up!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why ar'n't you gone, Madam? Do you think I'm not fit to be her champion?&mdash;Od&s;heart! though I'm not able to manage young women, I'll &s;hew you and your mi&s;tre&s;s I can be a match for old ones.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'm my own governe&s;s now!&mdash;Go, get along, De|borah!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Pu&s;hes her out.]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;Oh, Sir Solomon! if you were my grandfather, I couldn't be more grateful.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Read, read that letter!&mdash;I'm &s;orry to damp your joy. Albina.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What, does it bring bad news?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>The wor&s;t in the world.&mdash;Read, read! 'Tis written by Veritas.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb [Reads.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><Q>&startq;Sir, I am &s;o thorough a penitent, that I cannot be happy till. I have made a full confe&s;&s;ion of my bad inten|tions towards Mi&s;s Albina Mandeville. The truth is, I bound my&s;elf in an agreement with the Governe&s;s to give her half the Mandeville e&s;tate on the day of my marriage. And here. Sir, here was the cau&s;e of the much wronged Mr. Mandeville's ruin. To obtain this property, Mrs. Rigid gave out that he remitted no mo|ney for the &s;upport of his child, though to my know|ledge &s;he received a hundred and fifty pounds half-year|ly.&endq;</Q>&mdash;Sir Solomon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Go on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Reads]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P><Q>This &s;tory &s;o convinced the late Mr. &startq;Mandeville of his &s;on's inhumanity, that he died di&s;in|heriting him, and Albina lives to neglect the be&s;t of pa|rents.&endq;</Q>&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Drops the letter]</HI></STAGE>&mdash;I can't read any more&mdash;Oh, my poor father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You have for your excu&s;e youth and inexperi|ence&mdash;But I to be &s;uch a dupe!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where is he?&mdash;Where is my father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There again&mdash;there's another bad bu&s;ine&s;s!&mdash;He's no where to be found. Even Howard! knows nothing of him; for I met him ju&s;t now half di&s;tracted, &s;aying Mandeville had gone from the place where he left him, and,
<PB N="49" REF="49">pur&s;ued by his enemies, had fled either to London or the Continent. He called me a &s;avage&mdash;you another.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And well he might&mdash;Let's go after him!&mdash;We'll &s;earch the world over but we'll find him&mdash;Come, we'll hire all the hor&s;es, &s;ervants, and carriages in the county&mdash;We'll fly&mdash;We'll&mdash;Aw!&mdash;aw!&mdash;Here's the Go|verne&s;s! Do you &s;peak to her, for I can't.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Mrs. RIGID.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Solomon how dare you countenance my Pupil in di&s;obeying my orders?&mdash;Come along, Albina; be a good child, and go with your be&s;t friend&mdash;Why, what's the matter with you?&mdash;What does the girl make faces at?&mdash;Speak?&mdash;Are you ill?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Very loudly.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Heyday!&mdash;Do you know whom you're talking to?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Yes.&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Loudly.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fie, fie, Sir!&mdash;Teach a girl to in&s;ult her mother.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[to Sir Solomon.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Fie, fie, Madam&mdash;Teach a girl to de&s;ert her father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol. [turning her towards him]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where are the letters Mandeville wrote from India?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [turning her towards her]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where is the money he &s;ent for my &s;upport?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Peace! you little in&s;olent!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol. [turning her.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where is the agreement between you and the Tutor?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [turning her]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Where are a parent's affections&mdash;a &s;o|ver's heart?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Silence!&mdash;or I'll &s;o cha&s;ti&s;e you&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You cha&s;ti&s;e me!&mdash;The threats of my father or Mr. Howard would frighten me; becau&s;e they're good people, and injured people; and if you had behaved well, I had been &s;till afraid of you. But now&mdash;Oh! I wi&s;h I had a rod, I'd pay you off old &s;cores, that's what I would I&mdash;Come, Sir Solomon, let's leave her.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Aye: let us &s;eek out the wronged, the hone&s;t Mr. Maddeville!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> REALIZE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He's not to be found!&mdash;Mandeville's not to be found; and I &s;hall not only lo&s;e my two hundred pounds,
<PB N="50" REF="50">but &s;hall al&s;o be tricked out of my annuity&mdash;For yonder's Mr. Howard running about like a madman; and he &s;wears, if he don't find him he'll put an end to his exi&s;tence!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Sees Albina.]</HI></STAGE> Oh, ho!&mdash;Now we &s;hall get information!&mdash;Your &s;ervant, Mi&s;s&mdash;or rather Ma&s;ter, Albina!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Who's Governe&s;s now?&mdash;Didn't I tell you la&s;t night this lady was my mi&s;tre&s;s?</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Pointing to Mrs. Rigid.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You did.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>And isn't &s;he&mdash;isn't &s;he my mi&s;tre&s;s!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you like it.&mdash;If you prefer &s;erving her to me.&mdash;I'm &s;ure I've no objection.&mdash;So I give you warning, and appoint the Game-keeper your &s;ucce&s;&s;or.&mdash;Cop&s;ley &s;hall be Steward to the young lady&mdash;Mr. Realize to the old one.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Cop&s;ley become Steward!&mdash;Why, Governe&s;s!&mdash;Mi&s;tre&s;s!&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have you cut down that wood, Sir?&mdash;Oh, dear! That puts me in mind&mdash;I declare, Sir Solomon, I had quite forgot&mdash;There is a &s;tranger now at the Ca&s;tle, who can very likely give us intelligence about my father. He told me he was his friend; and he is &s;uch a kind, tender heart|ed creature!&mdash;We'll go there fir&s;t&mdash;Come.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Albina!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Mi&s;s Mandeville!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There, Madam, read that letter; and if you wi&s;h to avoid the mo&s;t exemplary puni&s;hment, look out all Mandeville's letters, and bring them to my hou&s;e directly.&mdash;You, al&s;o, Sir, bring your keys and papers at the &s;ame time!&mdash;Go this moment; and while Albina's at the Ca&s;tle, I'll wait your coming.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Sir Solomon!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No reply, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If I'm to lo&s;e my place, I hope I'm not to lo&s;e my money!&mdash;There's Mr. Mandeville's debt, two year's &s;a|lary, and a trifle due from Mr. Howard for the Bri&s;tol wa|ters.&mdash;He coughed me out of &agrave; do&s;e of phy&s;ic worth thirty pounds, Sir!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>No trifling!&mdash;Begone, Sir!&mdash;Mrs. Rigid, you know my determination.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stay!&mdash;This is the la&s;t time I &s;hall ever &s;ee her; and I can't bear to leave her &s;o unhappy.&mdash;Governe&s;s, though I'm a much greater object of pity than you are, yet
<PB N="51" REF="51">if my father will forgive you, I'm &s;ure I will.&mdash;At all events, while I have money, you &s;han't want.&mdash;Adieu!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Mrs. <HI>Rigid. [Weeping.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Farewell!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Real.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>P&s;ha! what &s;ignifies crying?&mdash;You &s;ee I'm not affected!&mdash;Nothing ever excites my &s;en&s;ibility but the touch of a guinea; and, thanks to my &s;teward&s;hip and the annuity trade! I've &s;aved enough to retire and live as a gentleman ought to do.&mdash;And &s;o, with many thanks for favours pa&s;t, your &s;ervant, young lady and old gentleman!&mdash;Come along, Governe&s;s! I &s;hall want a hou&s;e keeper; and &s;ince you can't be my mi&s;tre&s;s, I'll be your ma&s;ter!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[Exit with Mrs. Rigid.]</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Ah, you two hypocrites! begone!&mdash;Oh, So|lomon, Solomon, you ought to have known that a woman was at the bottom of all this mi&s;chief.&mdash;Come! I'll &s;ee you to the Ca&s;tle, and then&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay, Sir Solomon, if we meet Mr. Howard by the way, I hope you won't let him kill me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Kill you!&mdash;Why?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know he'll be mon&s;trous de&s;perate!&mdash;In a good cau&s;e I've a good heart; but, in a bad one&mdash;Oh, Lord!&mdash;Deborah is a lion to me!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Never fear: I'll &s;tand by you.&mdash;And to prove I can be a protector, without being a poacher, I'll not a&s;k even a ki&s;s, till I have delivered you &s;afe into your father's hands!&mdash;No!&mdash;And then I won't trouble you, unle&s;s you particularly de&s;ire it&mdash;Come&mdash;I've given all that up for life; and I &s;hall die as I have lived, a bachelor!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Don't! I hate bachelors&mdash;I wi&s;h there was a tax upon them.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There ought; for 'tis a luxury, I promi&s;e you.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Exeunt.</HI></STAGE>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 TYPE="scene">
<HEAD><HI>SCENE</HI>&mdash;The Baron's Chamber. Table remaining, with Pi&s;tol, &amp;c.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> How $word$</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not here, either!&mdash;No where to be found!&mdash;What can have become of him?&mdash;Veritas detained me longer than I intended; and when I returned to the ru|ins, Mandeville was gone; thinking, no doubt, that, like the re&s;t of his unfeeling friends, I had forgotten and de|&s;erted
<PB N="52" REF="52">him! I am the mo&s;t unhappy fellow living!&mdash; <STAGE><HI>Sits, his hand accidentally falls on the pi&s;tol]</HI></STAGE> What's here?&mdash;A pi&s;tol!&mdash;Oh, Heaven!&mdash;He couldn't be &s;o de&s;perate! How! the initials of his name upon the barrel! It is too evident&mdash;he has de&s;troyed him&s;elf, and died, &s;u&s;pecting Howard of ingratitude! I &s;hall not long &s;urvive him!&mdash;Oh, Mandeville! Mandeville!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand. [Within.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Howard! Howard!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What voice is that? Speak!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>'Tis I&mdash;'tis your friend!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He is living! <STAGE><HI>[tries the door.]</HI></STAGE> Nay: if 'twere adamant, I'd &s;plit it into atoms!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Forces it open.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MANDEVILLE.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard. [Embracing him.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My dear fellow! The next time you kill your&s;elf, don't leave your in&s;trument of death behind you. The initials on this barrel make the wor&s;t <HI>Mementy mori</HI> I ever read.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Kill my&s;elf! How you mi&s;conceive, my friend! I took refuge here to avoid Realize; and meeting young Herbert, he protected me, and locked me in that apart|ment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Did he? Did Bobadil protect you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He was mo&s;t kind to me; and promi&s;ed to make Albina kind to me. I wonder he's not returned; 'tis a long time &s;ince he left me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! he has a very &s;lippery memory!&mdash;The young coxcomb promi&s;ed to make Albina kind to me; and I've never &s;een nor heard of him &s;ince. However, to &s;hew you how very likely he is to keep his word with ei|ther of us. Albina by this time has left the Ca&s;tle, and gone to Dover.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Gone to Dover!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;aw the carriage at the door an hour ago. 'Sdeath! it's only lo&s;t time to think of her or Horbert! So, let us go to London&mdash;let us e&s;cape while we can.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well, be it &s;o. 'Tis plain I am forgotten&mdash;and therefore I, like Albina, will bid adieu to the Ca&s;tle for ever. And while &s;he hurries to &s;cenes of gaiety and hap|pine&s;s, her father &s;hall&mdash;No: while I have your friend|&s;hip, Howard, I ought, and will defy misfortune. <STAGE><HI>[Noi&s;e
<PB N="53" REF="53">of door opening.]</HI></STAGE> We are interrupted: &s;et us return to the chamber.</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>[Exeunt at the door Mandeville came from.]</HI></STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> ALBINA.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, dear! I'm &s;uch a coward!&mdash;Coming up &s;tairs, I thought I heard Mr. Howard's voice in this room; and I dread his reproaches, and his triumph, and his anger &s;o much, that I'd rather &s;ee the old Baron him&s;elf&mdash;Oh! it's all fancy&mdash;He's not here! So I may open the door, and venture to talk to my pri&s;oner&mdash;Heigho! the &s;ight of peo|ple one has injured is &s;o dreadful, that I do believe, if Mr. Howard&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[She opens the door.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> HOWARD.</STAGE>
<P>Oh! h! h!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Screams, and falls in his arms.]</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Holloa! What's the matter?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb. [Recovering.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nothing: I'm better now: I thought&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Well: what did you think?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I thought you had been the old Baron&mdash;But, I &s;ee&mdash;I &s;ee <STAGE><HI>[Stealing away from him by degrees.]</HI></STAGE> Good bye, Mr. Howard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Your &s;ervant.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>There! I &s;aid &s;o. I knew he'd be de&s;perate. Good bye Sir; I'm going!&mdash;Don't you &s;ee I'm going?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Going!&mdash;Why ar'n't you gone?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So I am&mdash;I am gone. Nay: you needn't be quite in &s;uch a hurry, Sir.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am in a hurry. I can't wa&s;te my time on doll$ and kick&s;haws.</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Turns his back to her.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! I was &s;ure this would be the ca&s;e!&mdash;What &s;hall I do? I've a great mind to take courage&mdash;to &s;um|mon up all my re&s;olution, and go boldly within ten yards of him. <STAGE><HI>[She advances, Howard turns, and frowns at her&mdash;She is frightened, and &s;tops. He turns his back again, and &s;he goes nearer to him.]</HI></STAGE> Lord! he takes it very quietly&mdash;I'll go clo&s;er. So&mdash;I dare &s;ay if I were to touch him he wouldn't bite my head off. Mr. Howard! How d'ye do, Mr. Howard?</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Pulls him round gently.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Keep off! or&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed I'm very &s;orry&mdash;I know I've behaved very
<PB N="54" REF="54">ill; but it was the Governe&s;s's fault, and not mine. Pray now forgive me&mdash;Look&mdash;on my knees I entreat you!&mdash;Forgive me this once, and I'll be &s;uch a good, dear, dar|ling girl!&mdash;I'll be your &s;lave&mdash;your doll&mdash;your kick&mdash; <STAGE><HI>[Howard &s;miles, and Albina jumps up.]</HI></STAGE> Oh, he &s;miles!&mdash;Your're a good natured creature, Howard! ha! ha!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Smiles, and looks in his face.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I don't &s;mile.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You do! you do!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I &s;ay I don't!&mdash;And hark'ye, if I were weak enough to forgive you on my own account&mdash;how&mdash;how would you apologize for your unnatural conduct to your father?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I'll &s;hew you&mdash;Look&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Takes a paper out of her pocket$]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What's that paper?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My grandfather's will!&mdash;Look!</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Smiling.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What!&mdash;Do you make a di&s;play&mdash;Do you boa&s;t of your ill-gotten wealth? Hear me! <STAGE><HI>[Lays hold of her hand $ith great emotion]</HI></STAGE> The Tutor has confe&s;&s;ed&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That Mr. Mandeville&mdash;that <HI>my</HI> friend&mdash;remit|ted money from India&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>That the Governe&s;s&mdash;that <HI>your</HI> friend&mdash;con|cealed his letters&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I know it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Then how dare you in&s;ult me with this ill|timed triumph? One word more, and we part for ever!&mdash;No chuckling!&mdash;Li&s;ten! <STAGE><HI>[Taking her hand with great vio|lence.]</HI></STAGE> If your grandfather had known the&s;e facts, would he have di&s;inherited an affectionate &s;on, only to adopt an unfeeling daughter? Would he not have de&s;troyed that te&s;tament?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>To be &s;ure he would! And as he can't do it him|&s;elf, won't I do it for him? There&mdash;and there&mdash;and there &mdash; <STAGE><HI>[tearing the Will.]</HI></STAGE> I'm my own mi&s;tre&s;s now; and I think I can't do greater honour to my grandfather's memory, than by de&s;troying an in&s;trument that he would now blu&s;h to &s;ign, and I for ever be a&s;hamed to profit by!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Are you&mdash;How hand&s;ome &s;he looks!&mdash;Are you convinced?</P>
</SP>
<PB N="55" REF="55">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I am: I hate my Governe&s;s as much for her un|cea&s;ing enmity to my father, as I envy you for your exalted friend&s;hip towards him!&mdash;Oh, Mr. Howard! Do you think he'll ever forgive me?&mdash;I'm going in &s;earch of him; but if you &s;hould be &s;o fortunate as to &s;ee him before me, pray tell him that things are now what they ought al|ways to have been&mdash;He is the po&s;&s;e&s;&s;or of the Mande|ville e&s;tate, and I have nothing but what re&s;ults from his bounty. Farewell!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Stay: it's my turn to kneel now! <STAGE><HI>[Kneels.]</HI></STAGE> Oh! you angel! <STAGE><HI>[Ri&s;es.]</HI></STAGE> Mandeville! Come forth, Mandeville. There is no longer any cau&s;e for concealing your&s;elf!
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> MANDEVILLE.</STAGE> Look at her! Look at Albina, your much-abu&s;ed daughter! She has parted from her Governe&s;s! She has torn her Grandfather's will! She has&mdash;Damn it! why don't you &s;peak to her? Joy choaks me! I'm dumb!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand. [Embracing her.]</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My child! My child!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>My father!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Have I at length a recompen&s;e? Oh, Howard! Did I not &s;ay the time would come?&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why will you &s;peak to me, when you know I can't an&s;wer you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will you forgive me, Sir? Can you forget&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Forget! I never blamed you. And at this mo|ment your mother's virtues &s;hine out &s;o brightly in your conduct, that I could wi&s;h that Will were &s;till in force. I want not now my father's wealth to make me happy&mdash;My child, my long-lo&s;t daughter is re&s;tored to me, and I am ble&s;t, and rich beyond my hopes!</P>
</SP>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> Sir SOLOMON, COPSLEY, <HI>and</HI> CICELY.</STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Come, Albina! 'Tis time to proceed on our journey. What, Mandeville! Howard! all together! all reconciled!&mdash;Tol de rol lol!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>So you're come to play the governor!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Not I. I've been as great a fool as any of you. I thought Mrs. Rigid a divinity, but I've found out &s;he's
<PB N="56" REF="56">a woman! Veritas has convented me. I'm a fair penitent now. Howard! Mandeville, you have de&s;erved better treatment;&mdash;give me your hand.&mdash;George, give me yours.&mdash;And now, my little fellow-traveller, give me the ki&s;s we talked of.&mdash;No: hang it! 'twill be only di&s;tre&s;&s;ing you!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, Sir Solomon, if it will give you any plea&s;ure, I'm &s;ure it will give me no pain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Arch rogue! Now I'll take it by proxy, on pur|po&s;e to be revenged. There, George, try how you can bear it <STAGE><HI>[Howard ki&s;&s;es Albina].</HI></STAGE> So, does it give you much pain? Well, what &s;ay you. Mr. Mandeville?&mdash;How &s;hall we puni&s;h the&s;e two culprits? Shall we inflict matrimony, or &s;eparation?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! Matrimony, by all means! Don't you think &s;o, Sir?</P>
<STAGE><HI>[To Mandeville.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Mand.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do, indeed! The day that gives Albina &s;uch a hu&s;band, and makes me father of &s;uch a &s;on as Howard, mu&s;t be the proude&s;t and happie&s;t of my life.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Say you &s;o? Then take her George! And if the marriage &s;tate can afford happine&s;s&mdash;However, we won't talk of impo&s;&s;ibilities.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Now, Albina, will you ever talk of Cicely again?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Will you ever call me Becky again?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Becky!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>If you do, I'll make you a companion to the wild goo&s;e in the cottage. "I hope your lungs are better, Sir?"</P>
<STAGE><HI>[Reminding him by her voice and attitude.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>What! Were you Bobadil? Were you the little &s;mart, well-made Lieutenant?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I was young Herbert, Sir; and I ble&s;s the di&s;gui&s;e, not only for convincing me of the &s;incerity of my lover, but al&s;o for introducing me to my father. I hope you don't blame me. Sir?&mdash;</P>
<STAGE><HI>[To Mandeville.]</HI></STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>He blame you! No: Howard has mo&s;t rea&s;on. What will your hu&s;band &s;ay to your &s;trutting about in boy's clothes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Say! That I wi&s;h all women would wear the breeches before marriage, in&s;tead of afterwards.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cop&s;.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, Madam! How &s;hall I thank you? You have &s;aved me and my family from ruin.</P>
</SP>
<PB N="57" REF="57">
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>You have, Madam! and we are all gratitude.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>This is your benefactor; you are to thank my fa|ther, not me. If you wi&s;h to do me a favour&mdash;why, there is one&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Cic.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Oh, name it, Madam! name it!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Why it rather concerns Sir Solomon than my&s;elf. Pray be kind enough to have the old curtain repaired, left he &s;hould again wi&s;h to take cover behind it. And like|wi&s;e, to &s;end me &s;ome of the &s;traw&mdash;I mean to be married in a &s;traw hat&mdash;and I'll have one manufactured out of Sir Solomon's &s;tubble!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>One! We'll have a dozen! And our children &s;hall wear them, in honour of their great uncle's gallantry!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sir <HI>Sol.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Gallantry! P&s;hal I've &s;omething better to think of than women.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Howard.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Indeed you have not. Come, come, Uncle&mdash;Rail at the &s;ex as much as you like, you mu&s;t confe&s;s, that life is a blank without them; and the gaming-table, the bottle, and the &s;ports of the field, are all &s;o many &s;ub&s;titutes&mdash;&s;hadows!&mdash;Woman is the true &s;ub&s;tance, after all&mdash;And, compared to her, all other objects are as the glow worm to the &s;un! It may dazzle the fight&mdash;but it can never warm the heart! Don't you think &s;o, Albina.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER><HI>Alb.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>I do, indeed. Women are certainly mo&s;t &s;uperior creatures; and, if by accident they have any faults, men ought not to &s;ee them&mdash;At lea&s;t, I hope that will be my ca&s;e to night. I have done and talked a great many foo|li&s;h things: but having their hands, and full pardon <STAGE><HI>[Standing between Mandeville and Howard];</HI></STAGE> let me have yours&mdash;and Albina will be the happie&s;t of wives, and the mo&s;t grateful of daughters.</P>
</SP>
<TRAILER>THE END.</TRAILER>
</DIV3>
</DIV2>
</DIV1>
</BODY>
