<DIV1 TYPE="epilogue">
<PB REF="58">
<HEAD>EPILOGUE.</HEAD>
<BYLINE><HI>Written by M. P. ANDREWS, <ABBR>E&s;q</ABBR></HI></BYLINE>
<P>SPOKEN BY MAS. JORDAN.</P>
<LG>
<L>THE World's a Stage&mdash;and Man has Seven Ages</L>
<L>So Shake&s;peare writes<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">The idea of this parody of the Seven Ages of Shake&s;peare, was &s;ugge&s;ted to Mr. Reynolds by his friend Mr. Rogers (Author of The Plea&s;ures to Memory), and the lines printed in Italies were furai&s;hed by him.</NOTE>&mdash;King of Dramatic Sages;</L>
<L>But he forgot to tell you in his plan,</L>
<L>That Woman plays her part as well as Man.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Fir&s;t, how her infant heart with triumph &s;wells,</HI></L>
<L><HI>When the red coral &s;hakes its &s;ilver hells!</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>She, like young Stote&s;$$en, as the rattle rings,</L>
<L>Leaps at the &s;ound, and &s;trum in leading-&s;trings.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Next, little Mi&s;s, in pin-a-fore &s;o trim,</L>
<L>With nur&s;e &s;o noi&s;y&mdash;with mama &s;o prim&mdash;</L>
<L>Eager to tell you all &s;he's taught to utter&mdash;</L>
<L>Li&s;ps as the gra&s;ps the allotted bread and butter;</L>
<L>Type of her &s;ex&mdash;who, though no longer young,</L>
<L>Hold every thing with ea&s;e&mdash;except their tongue.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>A School-girl then&mdash;She curls her hair in papers,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And mimics Father's gout, and Mother's vapours;</HI></L>
<L><HI>Tramples alike on cu&s;toms, and on toes,</HI></L>
<L><HI>And whi&s;pers all &s;he hears, to all &s;he knows:</HI></L>
<L>"Betty!" &s;he cries, "it comes into my head,</L>
<L>"Old maids grow cro&s;s becau&s;e their cats are dead;</L>
<L>"My Governe&s;s has been in &s;uch a fu&s;s</L>
<L>"About the death of our old tabby pu&s;s&mdash;</L>
<PB REF="59">
<L>"She wears black &s;tockings&mdash;Ha! ha!&mdash;What a "pother,</L>
<L>"'Cau&s;e one old cat's in mourning for another!"</L>
<L>The <HI>Child of Nature</HI>&mdash;free from pride and pomp,</L>
<L>And &s;ure to plea&s;e, though nothing but a <HI>Romp!</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Next riper Mi&s;s, who, Nature more di&s;clo&s;ing,</L>
<L>Now finds &s;ome traits of art are interpo&s;ing;</L>
<L><HI>And with blue laughing eyes behind her fan,</HI></L>
<L><HI>Fir&s;t acts her part&mdash;with that great actor, Man!</HI></L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Behold her now an ogling, vain Coquette,</L>
<L>Catching male gudgeons in her &s;ilver'd net:</L>
<L>All things revers'd&mdash;the neck, cropt clo&s;e and bare,</L>
<L>Scarce feels th' incumbrance of a &s;ingle hair;</L>
<L>Whil&s;t the thick forehead tre&s;&s;es, frizzled full,</L>
<L>Rival the tufted locks that grace the bull.&mdash;</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>Then comes that &s;ober character&mdash;a Wife,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With all the dear, di&s;tracting cares of life;</HI></L>
<L>A thou&s;and cards, a thou&s;and joys extend,</L>
<L>For what may not upon a card depend?</L>
<L>Though Ju&s;tice in the morn claim fifty pounds,</L>
<L>Five hundre won at night may heal the wounds!&mdash;</L>
<L><HI>Now &s;he'll &s;natch half a glance at Opera, Ball,</HI></L>
<L><HI>A meteor trac'd by none, though &s;een by all;</HI></L>
<L>Till Spou&s;y finds, while anxious to immure her,</L>
<L>A <HI>Patent Coffin</HI> only can &s;ecure her!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L><HI>At la&s;t the Dowager&mdash;in ancient flounces,</HI></L>
<L><HI>With &s;nuff and &s;pectacles, this age denounces</HI>&mdash;</L>
<L>And thus &s;he moralizes&mdash; <HI>[Speaks like an old woman.]</HI></L>
<L>"How bold and forward each young flirt appears!</L>
<L>"Court&s;hip, in my time, la&s;ted &s;even years&mdash;</L>
<L>"Now &s;even little months &s;uffice of cour&s;e,</L>
<L>"For courting, marrying, &s;colding, and divorce!</L>
<L>"What with their tru&s;s'd-up &s;hapes and pantaloons,</L>
<L>"Dre&s;s occupies the whole of honey-moons;&mdash;</L>
<PB REF="60">
<L>"They &s;ay we have no &s;ouls&mdash;but what more odd is,</L>
<L>"Nor men, nor women now have any bodies!&mdash;</L>
<L>"When I was young&mdash;my heart was always tender,</L>
<L>"And would, to every &s;pou&s;e I had, &s;urrender;</L>
<L>"Their wi&s;hes to refu&s;e I never dur&s;t&mdash;</L>
<L>"And my fourth died as happy as my fir&s;t."</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Truce to &s;uch &s;plenetic and ra&s;h de&s;igns,</L>
<L>And let us mingle candour with our lines.</L>
<L>In all the &s;tages of dome&s;tic life,</L>
<L>As child, as &s;ifter, parent friend, and wife,</L>
<L>Woman, the &s;ource of every &s;ond employ,</L>
<L>Softens affliction; and enlivens joy.</L>
<L>What is your boa&s;t, male rulers of the land?</L>
<L>How cold and cheerle&s;s all you can command!</L>
<L>Vain your ambition&mdash;vain your wealth and power.</L>
<L>Unle&s;s kind woman &s;hare your raptur'd hour;</L>
<L>Unle&s;s, 'mid&s;t all the glare of pageant art,</L>
<L>She adds her &s;mile, and triumphs in your heart.</L>
</LG>
